RamJam recently launched 'Southern Rail Tycoon' on Thursday, attracting 45,000 players to its satirical gameplay. In this light-hearted game, the objective is to prevent guards from boarding trains. Succeeding in this leads to service cancellations, from which players 'profit' by collecting virtual fares. The game draws its inspiration from the persistent train cancellations experienced over recent months, a result of an ongoing dispute with the RMT union. Players lose when a sufficient number of guards successfully board a train, causing the delayed service to finally depart.

Tom Jackson, a developer based in Brighton, shared his personal frustration, recounting how a planned trip to London a month prior was repeatedly delayed and then ultimately cancelled, leading his group to abandon train travel altogether. This frustrating experience prompted Mr. Jackson and his colleagues, Phil Hart and Toby Funnell, to create the game. The 39-year-old developer explained that the game serves a dual purpose: offering a fun distraction for commuters enduring train delays and raising awareness about the available compensation policies. Upon game completion, links are provided to Southern Rail's official compensation page and their Twitter account.

Jackson further elaborated that their studio enjoys creating games that are "reactive" to current events, demonstrating the "impact" news has on individuals. He described the train service as "an absolute shambles" and "incredibly frustrating".

A spokesperson for Southern Rail countered, stating that cancelling trains actually results in financial losses for them. They expressed efforts to provide the "best service possible under very difficult circumstances" and offered a "sincere apology".

The root of the ongoing issue lies in a dispute between the RMT union and GTR concerning the proposed increase in driver-only operated (DOO) services, which would alter the responsibilities of conductors. Due to regular strikes, Southern cancelled 341 daily train services on July 11, citing a need to improve "reliability." Since then, 15 of these services have been reinstated.

The continuous delays on the line, managed by Govia Thameslink Railway, led to the resignation of Rail Minister Claire Perry last Friday. The new Transport Secretary, Chris Grayling, declared on Monday that resolving the strike action was "top of his priority list".
Scarlets coach Wayne Pivac says he would be interested in talking to full-back Leigh Halfpenny "if he is serious" about returning to Wales.

Five CCTV cameras have been installed in rural locations throughout the city. Official data reveals 29,253 fly-tipping incidents occurred in West Yorkshire, costing councils Â¬Â£1.7 million to clear. Steve Hartley, Strategic Director for environment, stated their purpose is to gather evidence for prosecution. He added that these cameras are part of broader efforts to deter illegal dumping, apprehend culprits, and encourage responsible waste disposal. Council land litter is promptly cleared, with efforts also made to ensure private landowners do the same.
It's been another busy weekend in the Premier League.
Teenage Shrewsbury Town goalkeeper Callum Burton is still to determine what his future holds when his current contract runs out in June.

In Wrexham, specifically Bangor-on-Dee, three individuals were caught in a two-vehicle collision. A separate incident in Carmarthenshire saw one person hospitalized after an accident, while near Welshpool, a vehicle flipped over due to challenging conditions. On the Llanddulas coastal path in Conwy, two cyclists required medical attention after slipping on ice and falling from their bicycles.

Other incidents included a gritting truck overturning in harsh conditions and a school bus skidding on icy roads. Fortunately, the two occupants of the overturned lorry were uninjured. The vehicle came to rest on its side on the B4299, connecting Trelech and Bryn Iwan, on Tuesday evening shortly before 8 PM GMT.

Colin Evans from Carmarthenshire council confirmed that gritting vehicles would continue to be deployed as required. He added that the incident would not affect future gritting efforts, thanks to available reserve vehicles. Evans elaborated that "Gritting crews will stay on main routes until conditions are deemed safe. They will then proceed to secondary routes on elevated terrain, although a swift improvement in conditions is anticipated throughout the morning."

In Wattstown, within Rhondda Cynon Taf, a bus transporting six schoolchildren slid, narrowly avoiding a collision with a wall. Fortunately, no injuries were reported. Angela Slee recounted, "The sole factor preventing the bus from sliding further down the incline was a collection of rocks placed under its wheels by the bus escort." Separately, two individuals required hospital care after a tornado struck their residence.

Hanjin's board unanimously voted on Wednesday to file for court protection, a company spokesman confirmed. This decision follows the company's failure to convince key lenders to reschedule its debt under a new restructuring plan, leading to a severe cash shortage. Hanjin's shares remain suspended in Seoul, having plummeted by as much as 29% on Tuesday. The world's seventh-largest container line, Hanjin has reported unprofitability in four of the last five years.

Some financial reprieve for Hanjin may come from rival Hyundai Merchant Marine (HMM). HMM's shares surged by up to 22% after Korea's financial regulator indicated that the firm might acquire some of Hanjin's assets. Nevertheless, HMM has not been unaffected by the difficulties plaguing the sector, having recently announced its own reorganization strategy.

South Korea's shipping and shipbuilding industries are among those most severely impacted by a prolonged global trade downturn. A decline in orders has resulted in overcapacity, suppressed freight rates, and an escalation of debts. Nomura analyst Young Sun Kwon explained that Korean shipping companies have suffered substantial losses primarily because charter rates for leased vessels were fixed at high levels in 2010, while actual shipping rates have subsequently fallen.

The South Korean government is now preparing to implement a difficult, industry-wide restructuring, which will necessitate significant job cuts. Krystal Tan from Capital Economics stated that this ongoing restructuring is one reason why weak economic growth is anticipated this year and next. She added that the loss of tens of thousands of jobs would certainly negatively affect economic sentiment. However, she believes this number is relatively small when compared to the 26 million people employed in Korea, meaning a large increase in the unemployment rate is unlikely.

The Very Reverend Martin Thrower, the 56-year-old rector of Hadleigh, Suffolk, was accused in Norwich Crown Court of holding his mobile phone over a toilet cubicle. His arrest occurred in August 2016 at an Ipswich shopping centre. At a previous hearing, he pleaded guilty to two charges of voyeurism, receiving a 24-month suspended sentence. As part of his sentence, Thrower was ordered to complete a 60-day course specifically designed to address sex offending behavior, in addition to a further 30-day rehabilitation program.

Prosecutor William Carter explained that the rector was apprehended after a 17-year-old, using a toilet at the Buttermarket shopping centre, heard a sound above him. The teenager observed a hand holding a mobile phone that was filming him over the cubicle partition. He then seized the device, which led directly to Thrower's arrest.

When handing down the sentence, Judge Katharine Moore acknowledged Thrower's generally "well-regarded" status among those he had assisted, describing him as having been a "listening ear" in both "times of great sadness and some in happier times." She stated her perception that his "persistent behavior over a two-year period" had consistently been blamed on a decline in his mental health. While acknowledging his dedication to his work, she firmly rejected the notion that his actions were anything but deliberate choices, made repeatedly in public restrooms when he believed he would not be caught.

Upon his arrest, officers discovered three additional videos on his phone from that same day, two of which captured men seemingly unaware their privacy was being invaded.

Thrower, whose address is Church Street, Hadleigh, Suffolk, serves as the rector for Hadleigh, Layham, and Shelley parishes. The Diocese of St Edmundsbury in Ipswich has suspended him from all his duties. His legal counsel, Stephen Nelson, stated that Thrower was of previous good character and expressed his client's profound remorse.

Macauley Bonne put Colchester ahead in the 69th minute, but despite playing with ten men for over 70 minutes, Chesterfield quickly drew level from a penalty. Coach Keen, whose side is now without a league victory in 17 games, stated that teams are susceptible after scoring and stressed the need for much better game management. He added that mentally it's challenging when you haven't won in a long time. Colchester remain at the foot of the League One table, eight points behind 20th-placed Chesterfield. Midfielder Owen Garvan told BBC Essex there were "a few nerves out there" due to their winless run. He felt going ahead might calm them, but "the opposite happened and too many individual mistakes are costing us." Despite Gary Liddle's sending off and Bonne's goal, the U's allowed Lee Novak to convert from the spot after Richard Brindley fouled him. Garvan also voiced frustration over his team's lack of attacking inventiveness. "We had a lot of the ball, but we didn't make the keeper work too much. That's the most disappointing thing - we didn't create enough chances," he added, noting that simply playing long is "the easy option... counting on luck." He concluded that good teams must "break them down with good play - that's where our goal came from."

Scottish inmate Colin Capp, 23, assaulted his 45-year-old cellmate, Darren Thomas, as he slept in their Wing B cell.
Consultant forensic psychiatrist Dr. Melanie Croy testified to the jury that Mr. Capp's capacity for rational judgment was impaired by his mental illness. Mr. Capp admits to causing Mr. Thomas's death but denies murder.
Appearing for the defence, Dr. Croy, from Ashworth high-security hospital where Mr. Capp is detained, stated that he suffered from an abnormality of mental function, which could diminish his responsibility for Mr. Thomas's killing.
Dr. Croy further informed the court that Mr. Capp experienced paranoid delusional beliefs and heard two voices. One voice, identified as 'Mr. Grey,' reportedly instructs him to harm himself and others, the jury heard. She added that since his time at Ashworth Hospital, Mr. Capp has described voices commanding him to kill people with his bare hands. Conversely, a second, female voice acts as a protective guardian, offering him advice, the court was told.
Mr. Capp told Dr. Croy he believed he was being tortured at Cardiff prison in the weeks leading up to the incident and feared he would be killed.
In contrast, a separate consultant psychiatrist for the prosecution, Dr. Phillip Joseph, contended that Mr. Capp has a personality disorder rather than a mental illness. Dr. Joseph told the jury he believed Mr. Capp understood his actions when he killed his cellmate.
Mr. Thomas's body was discovered in the cell with a plastic bag over his head and approximately 100 stab wounds to the neck inflicted by a ballpoint pen.
Mr. Capp's defence rests on a plea of not guilty to murder due to diminished responsibility. The trial remains ongoing.
You might have seen pictures like these, empty homes in coastal areas that have slipped from cliffs that have become damaged.

The widespread sharing of Darren 'Birdie' Bird's poignant image, showing the mascot Pudsey paying tribute to Sir Terry Wogan who died on Sunday, has gained significant attention. The illustration itself features a tearful Pudsey with his characteristic eye patch depicted in black. Mr Bird, known as Birdie, admitted he was surprised by the drawing's immense reach. His initial tweet garnered over 3,000 shares, and the image has since been adopted as Children in Need's profile picture on both Twitter and Facebook, accumulating over 50,000 likes on the latter platform. The Ipswich-based cartoonist considered it an "absolute honour" that his artwork resonated with people and was perceived as a perfect homage to Sir Terry. While it was a "sad way" for his work to gain such exposure, he found the public's reaction and Children in Need's embrace "really lovely." Bird, whose prior work has appeared in the Racing Post and on Channel 4, expressed his long-standing admiration for Sir Terry as a "quick-witted" entertainer who "brought a lot of light into people's lives."

Vincent Kompany was instrumental in Manchester City taking the lead, pressuring Giorgio Chiellini into an own goal. However, Kompany sustained a calf injury as Juventus fought back to win 2-1. City manager Manuel Pellegrini stated Kompanyâs condition would be assessed on Wednesday to determine the severity of the injury. The 29-year-old Kompany was replaced by Nicolas Otamendi, Cityâs Â£32.5m signing from Valencia, after Mario Mandzukic equalised for Juventus. Alvaro Morata then scored the winning goal nine minutes from time.

Pellegrini also couldn't start striker Sergio Aguero due to a knee injury sustained during Saturday's win at Crystal Palace. The Argentina international made a seven-minute substitute appearance after City fell behind. Pellegrini explained Aguero was not fit for a full 90 minutes, deeming it too risky to play him extensively due to the potential for re-injury in the same area.

This defeat highlighted a persistent issue for City, who have yet to win their opening Champions League home game in five group stage attempts. Despite this, Pellegrini remains confident of reaching the last 16. Their next two matches are away trips against Germanyâs Borussia Monchengladbach and Spainâs reigning Europa League champions, Sevilla.

Pellegrini, who turns 62 on Wednesday, stressed that 15 more points are still available, and qualification depends on their performance and the results of their upcoming matches. He admitted losing at home to a strong side like Juventus was not an ideal start but emphasized that similar situations have occurred previously without preventing their progression.

Raheem Sterling was noted for missing a significant early chance and another when City were 1-0 up. However, Pellegrini downplayed the focus on Sterling, asserting that City had controlled the game. He described it as a "strange game" and felt City played better than Juventus, not deserving to lose. He acknowledged City's failure to convert chances, which is crucial in the Champions League, noting Juventus created fewer opportunities.

West Yorkshire Police recently admitted that 16,000 parking fines issued by their Police Community Support Officers (PCSOs) were invalid due to an "administrative error." However, the police stated that there were no legal grounds for issuing refunds, as such payments would have to come from public funds. A significant number of drivers paid these fines without questioning their legality. Following a review of PCSO authority in March, it was discovered that some PCSOs, who had joined the force years prior, had not been properly authorised to issue parking tickets from the outset. Police acknowledged in a statement that "an administrative error rendered the authorisation invalid." The force's records, accessible back to 2006, revealed that 16,000 tickets were impacted, leading to a total of Â£485,000 being paid into the courts. The force also conceded that other fines might have been issued under similar incorrect circumstances up to three years earlier. They confirmed seeking legal counsel on the issue. A spokesperson explained that, after legal assessment, they are confident there are no legal grounds for refunds, which would otherwise use public money. The core reasoning is that drivers had the opportunity to dispute the tickets' validity in court at the time, and penalties were only imposed on those found guilty. By choosing to pay the fine, motorists effectively accepted responsibility for the offence and forfeited their right to challenge it legally. The police confirmed that this "anomaly" has since been rectified, and PCSOs now possess the full authority to issue such fines.

Ahmed Mohamed's father, Mohamed El-Hassan Mohamed, has stated he withdrew all his children from schools in the area. According to Mr. Mohamed, the 14-year-old's arrest had a profoundly harmful effect. Ahmed's detention drew significant criticism, and the accusations against him were promptly dismissed. He was apprehended at MacArthur High School in Irving, Texas, when officials mistook a device he had brought for a "hoax bomb." "I don't want to go to MacArthur," Ahmed's father informed The Dallas Morning News on Tuesday, adding, "These kids won't be content there." Ahmed has received numerous school enrollment offers, his father stated, adding he wanted to give him a break before deciding. The entire family is scheduled to fly to New York on Wednesday, as United Nations dignitaries wish to meet Ahmed. Following that, Mr. Mohamed intends to take his son on a pilgrimage to Mecca in Saudi Arabia. "I pray Allah blesses this time. After that, we'll see," Mohamed commented. Upon their return, they plan to visit the White House to meet U.S. President Barack Obama, he added. Ahmed revealed his intention to transfer schools during a news conference last week. He told reporters it was "very upsetting" his teacher perceived his clock as a danger. "I constructed a clock to impress my teacher, but upon showing it to her, she believed it posed a threat. I am truly saddened that she misunderstood it." The apprehension of Ahmed Mohamed drew extensive condemnation, and the young boy has been met with widespread support, including a White House invitation.

Four men have pleaded not guilty to charges concerning the attempted smuggling of 35 people into Tilbury Docks, Essex. Tragically, one person died inside the container during this event.

At Basildon Crown Court, it was revealed that Timothy Murphy, one of the defendants from Londonderry, had been apprehended in France with migrants hidden in his lorry just 11 days prior to the Tilbury incident. He had been fined Â£5,000 in August for this earlier offense. Prosecutor Michael Goodwin told the court how, on August 5th, 12 Afghan individuals were discovered in a locker inside Mr. Murphy's lorry, which was transporting frozen chips from Coquelles, France, to the UK. Goodwin emphasized that their presence was not accidental, stating they "did not end up there by chance," implying deliberate placement. He added that Mr. Murphy maintained regular contact with co-defendants Stephen McLaughlin and Martin McGlinchey as he drove to Coquelles.

Eleven days later, on August 16th, the group of 35 Afghan Sikhs was located in the container at Tilbury. Mr. Goodwin recounted that dock workers heard noises from within and, upon opening it, found the occupants distressed and struggling for air. Meet Singh Kapoor, 40, tragically passed away during the overnight journey from Zeebrugge, Belgium.

Stephen McLaughlin (34, Limavady), Timothy Murphy (33, Elmgrove, Londonderry), Martin McGlinchey (47, Derryloughan Road, Coalisland, County Tyrone), and Taha Sharif (38, Kurdish, then living in Tottenham, London) have all entered not guilty pleas to charges of conspiring to facilitate illegal entry into the UK. The trial is projected to last up to six weeks.

Peter Clarke, the Chief Inspector of Prisons, released his findings following unannounced inspections. Key issues identified were insufficient staffing and a rise in the use of new psychoactive substances, which contributed to more erratic and aggressive conduct. However, inspectors also observed positive interactions between staff and prisoners, alongside a diverse array of training and educational opportunities. Although safety levels had worsened since 2013, Mr. Clarke characterized the situation as a complex blend of advancements and setbacks. During the July and August inspections, the prison held 770 inmates, significantly exceeding its Certified Normal Accommodation (CNA) capacity of 532, which indicates the number of prisoners that can be safely and humanely housed. Additional positive aspects noted in the report included better progress in rehabilitating inmates post-release. Conversely, some cells were in disrepair, and there was insufficient bedding. The report indicated that despite difficulties, the facility didn't feel unstable, and good staff-prisoner relations persisted. Michael Spurr, head of the National Offender Management Service, stated that even with considerable operational demands, the prison has maintained a constructive system offering ample purposeful activities and effective pre-release support for inmates. In contrast, the Howard League for Penal Reform, a campaign group, depicted it as an "overcrowded and understaffed facility where drug access is easy, but clean bedding is scarce." The recently implemented smoking prohibition was noted as being "unpopular among certain individuals." Frances Crook, the Howard League's chief executive, commented that while "this inspection report for Cardiff prison is marginally better than other recent prison reports we've reviewed, it still presents significant reasons for concern." Cardiff Central MP Jo Stevens, in her response, asserted that "this report plainly highlights major areas of concern for Cardiff prison, adding to the numerous warnings the Prisons Minister has received. The government must take urgent action."

Due to the upcoming general elections in India, commencing on May 12, the Twenty20 competition's schedule has been adjusted, as security personnel will be occupied. The initial phase of the tournament, from April 16 to April 30, will see a minimum of 16 matches played in the UAE. Following this, some second-stage fixtures are slated for Bangladesh. Once polling concludes, specifically from May 13, the competition will relocate to India for the remaining league games and play-offs. The IPL has requested government permission to host these later matches in various Indian states after their respective election phases end. The third and final phase, starting May 12 in India, will notably avoid May 16, which is designated for vote counting and election results. This scheduling change mirrors the 2009 IPL, which took place in South Africa due to electoral conflicts that year.

A life-sized bronze statue of Pocahontas stands in Gravesend, Kent, where she passed away in 1617 while journeying back to Virginia. Historic England has reaffirmed its Grade II listed status for this effigy, updating information regarding her life and role in Transatlantic history within its heritage list.

Furthermore, a monument in London has also been granted Grade II listed status. The Virginia Quay First Settlers Monument, situated in Blackwall across the River Thames from the O2 arena, commemorates the men, women, and children who set sail from that quayside for North America in December 1606. These adventurers subsequently founded Jamestown, Virginia, the first English colony, in April 1607, led by John Smith.

The statue of Pocahontas is a reproduction of a sculpture found in Jamestown, Virginia, which the state's then-governor donated to the UK in 1958. It was first officially listed in 1975.

Debbie Mays, Historic England's head of listing, commented, "Pocahontas is remembered for fostering connections between two vastly different cultures. These monuments act as physical reminders of her story, that of the English venturing to the New World, and our shared colonial past, and we are pleased to recognize their importance on the National Heritage List for England."

The team experienced a seven-wicket loss, having been dismissed for a mere 90 runs in a rain-shortened match at the Riverside. Speaking to BBC Newcastle, 29-year-old Rushworth confessed their performance was significantly inadequate. He acknowledged the reduced overs, but stressed that being bowled out for 90 in 22 overs was simply "not good enough." The squad has accepted that adjustments are necessary, either in their strategic approach or training methods. A four-and-a-half-hour rain interruption saw the game curtailed to 22 overs per side. This total was Durham's lowest against Worcestershire since they attained first-class county status in 1992. Mark Stoneman (29) and Paul Collingwood (17) were the sole batsmen to reach double figures. Sunderland-born Rushworth commented that while bowling conditions were favorable, batters must find ways to navigate difficult periods and accumulate runs. He highlighted the importance of consolidation over consistently attempting aggressive shots. To successfully pursue and overcome opponents, he stated, they "have to be able to put scores on the board." Durham's next fixture is Wednesday against Nottinghamshire. Rushworth added that alterations are vital, as Nottinghamshire have scored over 400 in their recent two games.

Updated 31 March 2015, 18:32 BST. Millie from Millie Inbetween hosts, exploring why our physical appearance is so important to many. Four children engage in an activity to assess their self-perception, while popstar Meghan Trainor shares her struggles with body image concerns. Explore more Newsround special programmes.
Numbers of harbour seals in Scotland have continued fall, according to a new report.
Artists including Missy Elliott, Kelly Clarkson and Kelly Rowland all feature on a charity single put together by US First Lady Michelle Obama.

Heavyweight boxing champion Tyson Fury, 27, known for his opinions on women, abortion, and homosexuality, has been summoned to a meeting with the British Boxing Board of Control (BBBofC) early next year. The BBBofC decided this after a Wednesday discussion. Fury denies being homophobic, asserting he is "uniting the world," though no precise date for the meeting has been set.

Meanwhile, Fury will not face criminal charges from Greater Manchester Police (GMP) regarding alleged homophobic remarks. GMP received a complaint about his statements on the BBC's Victoria Derbyshire programme but classified them as a "hate incident" rather than a "hate crime."

Following his victory over Wladimir Klitschko in Dusseldorf, Fury stated: "I'm not sexist. I believe a woman's best place is in the kitchen and on her back. That's my personal belief. Making me a good cup of tea, that's what I believe." The new world champion had also previously claimed that the legalisation of paedophilia, alongside the decriminalisation of homosexuality and abortion, would signal "the devil come home." Subsequently, the Manchester-born fighter clarified, "Tyson Fury loves his fellow humans. He doesn't hate anybody."

Greg Rutherford, a fellow nominee for BBC Sports Personality of the Year and a long jump champion, initially intended to withdraw from the event due to Fury's comments but later changed his mind. Furthermore, Fury, who captured the WBA, IBF, and WBO titles on November 28 by defeating Klitschko, was stripped of his IBF belt on Tuesday. This occurred because he opted for a rematch with Klitschko instead of fulfilling the IBF's mandatory defence against Ukrainian Vyacheslav Glazkov.

Fifty-year-old McAuley, residing at Cavan Bank Walk, Ballyconnell, County Cavan, admitted guilt to two charges stemming from an incident on December 24 last year. He pleaded guilty to brandishing a knife during an altercation in Kilderry, Kilnaleck, Cavan, and to issuing death threats against his estranged wifeâs brother, Tommy Tully, during the same event. McAuley's only words were confirming his guilt. The judge ordered McAuley held at Castlerea prison until his sentencing hearing at Cavan Circuit Court on November 24. Furthermore, the court requested a victim impact report for Ms Tully and a probation and welfare report for McAuley.

Ashley Broomhall recently completed challenging mountain climbs, first scaling 3,560ft (1,085m) Snowdon in Snowdonia before undertaking the 4,406ft (1,344m) Ben Nevis near Fort William, Scotland. The ascent and descent of Ben Nevis took him seven hours. He now plans to hike 3,208ft (978m) Scafell Pike in the Lake District.

Mr. Broomhall, a 28-year-old from Whitchurch in Shropshire, is tackling these peaks to generate funds for Cancer Research UK, a personal mission inspired by his mother's cancer diagnosis. For over five years, he has been a member of the 501st UK Garrison, a Star Wars costuming club whose members attend events across the UK in "movie-accurate" outfits to raise money for various charities.

For his summer ascents of Snowdon and Ben Nevis, Mr. Broomhall adapted his Imperial stormtrooper costume for improved flexibility during the climbs. Prioritizing safety, he opted for regular walking boots instead of his costume footwear, which was unsuitable for the demanding terrain, and was accompanied by friends.

While climbing Ben Nevis, Scotland's highest Munro and Britain's tallest mountain, dressed as a stormtrooper and proudly carrying a UK Garrison flag, Mr. Broomhall garnered significant attention. He noted that other climbers were often bewildered by the sight of a stormtrooper on the mountain, an unexpected encounter. He handed out cards explaining his purpose, receiving enthusiastic support and donations from fellow trekkers.

Higher on Ben Nevis, he navigated through sections of thigh-deep snow. At one of these snowy expanses, he and his walking companion engaged in a playful snowball fight with other hikers. Upon reaching the final snowfield that led to the summit, Mr. Broomhall described a surge of pride as he charged forward with the flag. Greeted by cheers from climbers already there, he triumphantly planted his flag, symbolically claiming the summit for the "Empire." He expressed his enjoyment of the challenge and his affection for Scotland and its Munros, declaring his intention to conquer Scafell Pike also in his distinctive armour, having successfully done so for the first two peaks.
Kris Meeke edged out Sebastian Ogier to lead by 10.3 seconds after the first day of the World Rally Championship round at Corsica.

Merseyrail intends to launch a new fleet of 52 trains, designed for driver-only operation (DOO), starting in 2020. The company stated that no permanent guards or guard managers would face compulsory termination of their employment. The RMT union, however, announced it was in a formal dispute with Merseyrail, indicating its 220 members would be balloted for strike action. John Tilley, an RMT representative, stated that Merseyrail failed to provide solid assurances regarding the future of 220 guards and managers during a meeting on Wednesday, expressing his strong expectation that members would vote overwhelmingly for industrial action. RMT General Secretary Mick Cash affirmed the union's refusal to accept any expansion of DOO, committing to a fight to preserve the guard's crucial safety role and ensure a guard remains on every train. He added that the train operator had "snubbed" a final opportunity to prevent the ballot. Cash further commented that the situation was "entirely preventable if the company had listened to the union's profound safety concerns... and had prioritized passenger safety over profit." Merseyrail, for its part, asserted it had "made it clear" it would support guards and management whose positions would cease to exist with the new fleet's introduction, confirming there would be no compulsory redundancies. The train operator explained that while the RMT had insisted on a guard on every new train, the new fleet was designed to operate without guards, making it impossible for them to fulfill this demand. Merseyrail's existing fleet, although based on designs from the 1950s, is nearly 40 years old.

Scotland's Anderson posted an average of 107.68, the highest recorded in the tournament so far, outperforming his Dutch rival's 102.3. Together, the two competitors also landed 20 maximum 180s at London's Alexandra Palace.

In a thrilling encounter, Dutchman Raymond van Barneveld, seeded 12th, defeated fifth seed Adrian Lewis 4-3 to advance to the quarter-finals. Both players are former champions. Lewis, who had been beaten by Anderson in last year's final, initially held a 3-2 lead against Van Barneveld before the 2007 champion rallied to win.

Earlier, in the second round, third seed Peter Wright of Scotland secured a dominant 4-0 victory over Wales' Jamie Lewis. Wright lost just one leg during the match, achieving an impressive 75% checkout percentage.

Other second-round results included Belgium's Kim Huybrechts' 4-0 win against Germany's Max Hopp. Sixth seed James Wade, from England, overcame fellow Englishman Steve Beaton 4-1, and the Netherlands' 10th seed Jelle Klaasen also triumphed 4-0 against Northern Ireland's Brendan Dolan.

Glenfield Hospital's East Midlands Congenital Heart Centre is set to discontinue its children's surgical services, an announcement made on Wednesday. This decision stems from a national review of ten units, aiming to consolidate specialist expertise into fewer locations. The charity Heartlink swiftly expressed its opposition to this judgement. John Rigby, a Heartlink spokesman, stated their intention to "take stock, listen to what our reps have to say and be guided by them," vowing to "fight to do our very best to keep children's services here [at Glenfield]."

Annually, the centre performs around 230 operations on children and 70 on adults. It also boasts the UK's largest ECMO unit, which provides partial cardiopulmonary bypass to oxygenate the blood of critically ill patients. Although pediatric surgeries will cease, the unit will remain open for patient diagnosis, monitoring, and non-surgical treatments.

Serving a population of approximately five million, the centre's closure means the next comparable facility is in Birmingham, roughly 40 miles (64.4 km) away. Leslie Hamilton, vice-chair of the Safe and Sustainable review's steering group, articulated the surgical community's concern that expertise was too thinly spread across the country. He explained the rationale for consolidation: "We felt we had to concentrate the expertise and reduce the number of centres in the country so we could have bigger centres with bigger surgical teams. That would lead to sustainable care for the future and also a big improvement in care."

Tony Fowlston's three-year-old son, Lewis, has been a patient at Glenfield. The family regularly travels about 60 miles (96.5 km) from Boston, Lincolnshire, to access specialists. Mr. Fowlston highlighted that further travel could pose a serious risk, given Lewis recently suffered a cardiac arrest shortly after arriving at Glenfield. He critically questioned the alternative: "He could have had that cardiac arrest on the way to, say, Birmingham. Could he have had the same service in the back of an ambulance? I very much doubt it." A petition to save the unit garnered more than 100,000 signatures.

Foreign Minister Hina Rabbani Khar's statements came just hours after top military operational commanders of India and Pakistan agreed to reduce mounting tensions. This development follows fatal exchanges along the border last week, which have plunged the two neighbouring countries into their most severe crisis since the 2008 Mumbai attacks, widely attributed to Pakistan-based militants.

Ms. Khar's office advised against aggressive remarks from military and political leaders across the border that escalate tensions. Instead, it suggested that both nations should engage in discussions concerning all issues related to the Line of Control (LoC) to reinforce adherence to the ceasefire. AFP quoted her saying the recent border skirmishes "created questions," and affirmed Pakistan's openness to dialogue between foreign ministers to resolve the dispute. India has not yet responded to Ms. Khar's comments.

On Wednesday, Pakistan's director of military operations consented to de-escalation after contacting his Indian counterpart to "strongly protest" an alleged "ceasefire violation" by Indian troops that killed a Pakistani soldier along the LoC on Tuesday night. India has denied this accusation, which follows other incidents last week where two Indian and two Pakistani soldiers lost their lives. An Indian army spokesman, Col Jagdeep Dahiya, informed the BBC that the Pakistani commander affirmed issuing strict directives to troops stationed at the LoC to uphold the ceasefire established in 2003.

Both sides deny provoking the recent clashes, amidst fears, as reported by the BBC's Sanjoy Majumder in Delhi, that a nascent peace initiative, underway since last February, could unravel. Earlier, on Tuesday, Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh had labeled the killing of Indian soldiers last week â with India alleging one was beheaded â as "unacceptable." Kashmir, claimed by both nations, has remained a flashpoint for over six decades, resulting in two wars. While cross-border firing in this disputed area is common, it rarely leads to fatalities.

Dave Cormack, who previously served as Aberdeen's chief executive, recently sold his software company for Â£630 million. He informed the Aberdeen website that he would contribute both financially and with his time, aiming to draw in US investment and form strategic alliances to help the club reach its full potential. Cormack will collaborate with the current board, including chairman Stewart Milne, dividing his time between Atlanta and North East Scotland. The 58-year-old previously held an interim chief executive role at Pittodrie from 2000 to 2001, while on a break from his business ventures in the United States. He intends to work alongside the AFC management team to implement innovative strategies he's observed succeeding in the US. His return follows the sale of a software company he significantly expanded, growing its team from 12 employees in 2004 to 500 by 2016, and generating Â£107 million in yearly revenue. Cormack stated his honor at rejoining the board, noting he had consistently supported and advised the club for years. He commended the dedication of everyone at Pittodrie, evidenced by the club's strong performance both athletically and administratively in recent seasons. He acknowledged the fortunate position of having a high-performing, debt-free team, but stressed the necessity of capitalizing on opportunities to boost income and expand the fanbase. He expressed eagerness to collaborate with the current leadership team, with whom he shares a strong rapport. Cormack is confident that, working together and with fan support, they can enhance the club's financial standing, enlarge its supporter base, and develop a modern community stadium and training complex, enabling AFC to effectively leverage developments in European club competitions. Chairman Stewart Milne expressed his welcome for Cormack's engagement and the wealth of experience he brings. Milne highlighted the growing complexity of managing a modern football club, stating that Dave's expertise, background, enthusiasm, and dedication would be highly advantageous. He added that Cormack offers fresh insights, an innovative methodology, and valuable business acumen to confront current challenges directly.

Authorities suspect a female Islamic State suicide bomber was responsible for the explosion. This attack comes as Turkey intensifies its efforts against militants, a shift from past accusations of inaction. The explosion provoked violent demonstrations in Istanbul, where police deployed water cannons, teargas, and rubber bullets. The bomb, which occurred on a Friday, targeted young activists preparing to travel to Syria to assist in the reconstruction of Kobane. Footage reveals the group, predominantly university-aged individuals, at a cultural center's grounds holding a press conference about their initiative when the blast occurred. They were chanting slogans and displaying a banner proclaiming, "We defended it together, we are building it together." Kobane, situated across the border from Suruc, was a scene of intense conflict between IS and Kurdish forces, with Kurds reclaiming it in January. Suruc currently hosts numerous refugees who escaped the violence in Kobane. The attack occurred shortly before noon local time (09:00 GMT), injuring approximately one hundred people. Prime Minister Davutoglu stated that preliminary evidence pointed to IS as the perpetrators. Addressing a news conference in Ankara, he affirmed Turkey's ongoing commitment to implement all essential counter-terrorism measures against Islamic State. He emphasized confronting a "terrorism incident" and the determination to identify and punish those accountable, also indicating an increase in security measures along the Syrian border. BBC Middle East correspondent Jim Muir notes that Turkey, widely criticized for previously overlooking IS operations, has recently intensified its efforts against the militants, which could be a motive for the assault. He anticipates that Turkish leadership will likely adopt an even stricter stance following this event. Widespread demonstrations erupted in cities nationwide. Protests in Istanbul and Ankara escalated into violence, resulting in clashes with police. According to a Reuters witness, hundreds of Istanbul protestors chanted slogans alleging Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan's cooperation with IS. Earlier, while in Cyprus, the President denounced the attack, stating, "On behalf of my people, I curse and condemn the perpetrators of this brutality." He added that "Terror must be condemned no matter where it comes from." A White House spokesperson also condemned the attack, expressing "solidarity with the Turkish government and the Turkish people."

At approximately 15:10 BST, the Welsh Ambulance Service responded to a 999 call, transporting an injured person to Prince Charles Hospital in Merthyr Tydfil. The road between Cefn Coed roundabout and B4276 Merthyr Road is closed in both directions due to this incident. The individual's current condition remains unknown. Motorists should check for travel disruptions.

The government intends to modify an RAF Voyager A330 air-to-air refuelling aircraft for an estimated cost of Â£10 million. This adaptation is projected to save approximately Â£775,000 annually, as the plane will be a more economical alternative to chartering flights. Stewart Hosie of the SNP stressed the necessity of "absolute transparency" to ensure taxpayers receive the "best deal." He also pointed out the announcement's timing, just a week before a spending review expected to unveil more "Tory cuts" that are already severely affecting the public. Indeed, most government departments are facing budget reductions of at least 25% over the next four years. A source indicated that the Prime Minister's current flights, whether on Royal Squadron planes or long-haul charters, cost an average of Â£6,700 per flying hour. In contrast, the adapted RAF aircraft would cost around Â£2,000 per hour and would still be available for refuelling when not in use for transport. The Royal family would also have access to this aircraft. This move echoes a previous plan by Tony Blair to purchase two private jets, controversially nicknamed "Blair Force One" after the US President's plane, which was subsequently cancelled by his successor, Gordon Brown. Further details about these new arrangements are expected during Monday's strategic defence and security review. While no definitive in-service date for the plane has been set, it could become operational as early as next year. A government spokesperson elaborated that as part of the defence review, they have been investigating how to better utilize the RAF fleet for ministerial transport and achieve taxpayer savings. They confirmed the decision to adapt an existing Voyager, allowing it to transport ministers and be available to the Royal family, in addition to its primary air refuelling role.

The leader of Plaid Cymru, writing in the Sunday Times, called for Wales to present a united front. A confrontation is anticipated between the UKIP leader and the Welsh First Minister during a Cardiff event on Monday. A national referendum concerning the UK's continued membership in the European Union is scheduled before the end of 2017. Ms. Wood acknowledged that calls for EU reform were valid, but emphasized that the advantages of EU membership for Wales' agriculture, higher education, and transport significantly surpassed any disadvantages. She condemned Prime Minister David Cameron's decision to permit ministers to campaign on either side of the referendum, labelling it "irresponsible and bizarre." Furthermore, she stated that this issue would fundamentally change the nature of the discussion leading up to the Welsh National Assembly elections on May 5th.

The 19-year-old Harry Dearden and Paul Horton (41) forged an 85-run opening partnership before Glamorgan swiftly claimed three wickets, two of which were taken by young Lukas Carey. Dearden then spearheaded a valuable 90-run stand with Mark Pettini (who remained 63 not out) until spinner Andrew Salter dismissed him. Under the floodlights, Pettini then guided the Foxes to secure their second batting point. Despite being dropped when he had just one run and narrowly escaping two potential run-outs, Deardenâs resilient vigil lasted 211 balls. This was a gritty batting display from the home side, who were asked to bat first in a contest between two teams that had both suffered significant defeats in their opening two fixtures. Salter secured his second wicket, bowling Cameron Delport for 20, after which Pettini and Lewis Hill rapidly added 73 runs, capitalising on the new ball.

Speaking to BBC Radio Leicester, Leicestershireâs Harry Dearden commented: "I'm incredibly proud of achieving my career-best score. While I had hoped to reach a century, I'm still very proud of this performance, which has made it a truly positive day for us. The conditions were challenging early on, with the ball moving off the pitch and swinging. The key was to face as many deliveries as possible to settle in, and it was a tough contest against their opening bowlers. My focus was on digging deep and maintaining maximum discipline. Batting with Horts (Paul Horton) is beneficial as his experience provides a calming influence, and it's also excellent to bat alongside Mark (Pettini) because he helps you stay balanced."

Glamorgan spinner Andrew Salter shared his thoughts with BBC Wales Sport: "I'm pleased to have taken those two wickets, though it wasn't surprising that there wasn't much spin â one delivery went straight through, and the other, a bit fuller, found some rough. My primary aim was to control the scoring rate, believing that sustained pressure would eventually yield rewards. Therefore, I hope my services won't be required significantly more in this first innings. Overall, our bowling unit performed exceptionally well for most of the day; Lukas (Carey) was outstanding at the start. The run-rate was kept to 2.6 for a significant portion of the day, and it was only towards the close that they managed to increase their scoring."

The 27-year-old former England youth international, who left Sunderland last season, previously played for Chelsea and Everton. Royals boss Kelly Chambers hailed her as "a truly exciting signing." Chambers added, "She's a prolific scorer who will definitely enhance our attacking options and perfectly suits our style of play."

The concept for the event reportedly emerged at 2 PM. Following intense speculation and several location changes, tickets for the Koko venue in Camden became available at 7 PM. Despite waiting for hours in the cold, the audience didn't see Kanye perform until approximately 1:20 AM. He was accompanied onstage by Skepta, JME, Novelist, Vic Mensa, Meridian Dan, Raekwon, and Cyhi. Radio 1's Clara Amfo, who attended, described the scene as "ridiculous," with "hordes of people outside," calling it "crazy." Access to the venue for fans began around 12:45 AM, though Kanye's performance didn't commence until over half an hour later. Grimmy expressed disappointment at missing the event, citing his need to "get up and do the radio [Radio 1 breakfast show]." Nevertheless, he admired its spontaneous nature, commenting, "I love that it was like, panic, it's exciting it's tonight." Clara informed Grimmy that Kanye "smashed it." She added that "He's like trolling the UK right now and I totally fell for it." Beyond performing classic hits such as "Jesus Walks" and "Clique," he also gave a sneak peek of his latest collaboration with Vic Mensa. Mistajam from 1Xtra was also in attendance, tweeting, "Tonight will go down in history." For more updates, follow @BBCNewsbeat on Twitter and Instagram, and Radio1Newsbeat on YouTube.

Josh Taylor, the Commonwealth gold medallist, competed for the first time before his home supporters at a packed Meadowbank. Taylor expressed surprise at how quickly the bout concluded. His manager, Barry McGuigan, hailed Taylor as "very special," stressing the importance of selecting opponents carefully and at the right moment.

The Hungarian opponent, Mate, entered the contest with an impressive record of 17 wins from 22 previous fights. However, it was immediately clear that Taylor was far superior. Taylor charged from his corner, sending Mate to the canvas within just 45 seconds. A subsequent left hook from the Commonwealth Games champion floored Mate once more, prompting the referee to intervene and stop the fight after only 85 seconds of the first round, sparing Mate from further punishment.

Taylor admitted he was taken aback by the swift victory, having anticipated a more challenging bout in front of his home crowd. He commented on the hostile atmosphere, sensing Mate's apprehension in the ring and his own superior power.

McGuigan, a former world champion, remarked that the fight offered little new insight into his boxer's abilities. He described it as a "pretty unproductive exercise" since Taylor didn't get the expected number of rounds, but reaffirmed Taylor's formidable punching power, noting Mate's inability to recover from the knockdown.

Moving forward, McGuigan stated a tougher opponent would be sought for Taylor's next contest. He acknowledged Taylor's high skill level and stressed the need to find opponents of even higher caliber. Taylor, meanwhile, plans to return to the ring before the end of the year, deferring any potential title fights for the time being. He intends to take only a brief break before resuming training, aiming to further his professional development and gain more rounds, even though his amateur background already places him at a domestic title level.

Manchester United's new Â£75m signing, 24-year-old Belgian striker Romelu Lukaku, netted the winning goal seven minutes before halftime. This followed Henrikh Mkhitaryan's earlier equaliser, after United had initially conceded in the 20th minute. The match also saw United suffer setbacks with Juan Mata's injury and Antonio Valencia's red card.

Manager Mourinho commented that while Lukaku's goal was "nice for him," it held little importance to him personally. He added, "I told him I love what he does," praising the striker's assists, movement, and ability to hold up the ball, concluding, "I like everything he does."

Mata's departure was due to a strong challenge from Sebastian Saucedo, though he's only expected to miss up to a week of play. Later, Valencia received a red card for a tackle on Saucedo. Referee Allen Chapman initially consulted with Mourinho before finally sending off the Ecuadorian. Mourinho explained the delay: "The referee asked me to change the players and I didn't because I don't agree with the card." The Old Trafford manager further claimed Saucedo had been "really aggressive with what happened to Mata and some other actions where he was a bit dangerous," but dismissed it as "pre-season so no problem - it's a good experience."

United's next fixture is against rivals Manchester City in Houston on Friday morning UK time (02:30 BST).

BBC Sport's Simon Stone in Utah commented on the incident, suggesting referee Allen Chapman was compelled to act after Valencia's forceful tackle on Saucedo. Chapman, notable as the first video assistant referee to make a live decision in a 2016 USL game, reportedly first glanced at Jose Mourinho. After ensuring Saucedo was attended to, he approached the United manager, requesting Valencia be substituted, seemingly cautious about dismissing a player in a friendly. When Mourinho declined, Chapman, "almost apologetically," proceeded to issue the red card to the Ecuadorian.

A Royal Air Force plane from the Rhodesian Squadron, stationed at RAF Wittering, crashed in Holme on November 22, 1940. Pilot Officer Harold Penketh, a Brighton native, tragically died without bailing out. The aircraft's remains, identified as a Spitfire, were discovered following a geophysical survey of the site. There is an expectation that the salvaged components will eventually be exhibited publicly. Although the precise cause of the crash was never definitively determined, eyewitnesses reported that the Mk 1A Spitfire, serial number X4583, broke away from its formation and plunged nose-first into agricultural land in the village of Holme, located south of Peterborough. An investigation concluded that either the pilot's oxygen supply system failed or the aircraft itself experienced a structural malfunction. The 20-year-old Pilot Officer Penketh apparently made no attempt to deploy his parachute. His body was recovered from the debris and subsequently returned to his relatives. John Bliss, an eyewitness who was a child at the time, recounted that the "enormous crater" formed by the Spitfire's impact rapidly filled with water due to the area's high water table. For 75 years, the Spitfire's wreckage lay submerged in its watery resting place. Cranfield University successfully located the crash site in August, using a combination of a geophysical survey and metal detection. The excavation, commencing on Monday and anticipated to last a week, is being overseen by Oxford Archaeology East. The retrieved components, which remain the property of the Ministry of Defence, will undergo cleaning and documentation. Portions of them are slated for public exhibition later this month. Once the excavation concludes, the land will be reinstated as diverse fenland habitats and managed as part of the Great Fen reserve by the Wildlife Trust for Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, and Northamptonshire.
A Swansea-based artist is using waste which has washed up on nearby beaches in her new exhibition.
Two men have been charged with child pornography crimes in the alleged cyber-bullying of a teenaged Canadian girl who later took her own life.

Scrum-half Rhys Webb is set to return to the Welsh squad from the bench, marking his first appearance since suffering a foot injury last September. Gareth Davies affirmed that Webb's immediate return was anticipated once he regained fitness, noting that the added competition creates "a bit of extra pressure" which he finds enjoyable.

Currently, England leads Wales by one point at the top of the table, having secured three victories from three games. Both players have a history of impactful performances against England: Webb famously scored a try in Wales' 2015 Six Nations win in Cardiff, while Davies delivered a crucial late try in their 2015 World Cup victory, a tournament Webb missed following surgery. Davies, 25, has accumulated six tries in 12 Wales appearances, in contrast to 27-year-old Webb's five tries in 16 games.

Under new coach Eddie Jones, England boasts an unblemished record. Wales, meanwhile, rebounded from an opening draw in Ireland to defeat Scotland and France. If England overcomes Wales, they will travel to France on March 19th, aiming for their first Grand Slam since 2003. Conversely, a Welsh triumph on Saturday would position them to win the championship for the third time in five years by simply defeating Italy at home.

Davies admitted that Wales has started some games in this campaign slowly. He stressed the importance of the initial 20 minutes, stating, "We have got to come out all guns blazing. That is going to be massive for us." He also conveyed confidence in playing on any ground, referencing their strong performances at Twickenham during the World Cup as evidence that it is "not a place we are scared to go."

According to PwC's yearly survey, only 37% of respondents anticipate economic improvement in 2015, a decrease from 44% in the previous year. Unsurprisingly, Russian executives, once the most optimistic, are now the least so, a shift attributed to sanctions and declining oil prices. In the United Kingdom, there has been a significant increase in apprehension regarding talent availability. The percentage of CEOs in the UK worried about skill shortages jumped from 64% last year to 84% this year, a rate significantly exceeding that in Germany, France, or Spain. This escalating concern is partly attributed to the UK's high employment rates, which reduce the available talent pool, and partly to worries about the quality of the education system. Globally, the primary concerns for chief executives include geopolitical instability, excessive regulation, and cyber security threats. The report, unveiled at the World Economic Forum in Davos, highlighted that apprehension concerning cyber threats has risen more than any other issue since last year, noting that recent attacks on gaming and entertainment networks are expected to further elevate this perceived risk. Dennis Nally, PwC's chairman, commented that CEO confidence has significantly declined in oil-producing countries globally, primarily due to collapsing crude oil prices. He cited Russian CEOs as a prime example, shifting from being the most confident in the prior year's survey to the least confident this year. Nally added that executives in the Middle East, Venezuela, and Nigeria have also experienced a drop in confidence. Furthermore, he observed a noticeable transfer of confidence from emerging markets towards Western economies. For the upcoming year, chief executives identified the United States as their top market for growth, surpassing China for the first time since this question was introduced five years ago. PwC conducted this survey by interviewing over 1,300 chief executives across 77 nations during the last quarter of 2014.

A violent clash resulted in the deaths of six police officers and eleven protestors during an operation to remove farmers from land they had occupied. These fatalities escalated political tensions in Paraguay, subsequently leading to President Fernando Lugo's removal from office by congress.

In the aftermath, four men were sentenced to 18 to 30 years in prison, with an additional seven individuals (men and women) receiving jail terms of four to six years. Testimony revealed the confrontation took place near Curuguaty, in eastern Paraguay's Canindeyu province. Approximately 250 riot police were dispatched to clear about 70 subsistence farmers from a Campos Morumbi agricultural company property. The farmers had been occupying the land to advocate for agrarian reform.

Notably, the Paraguayan prosecution service failed to investigate the farmers' deaths, and both local and international human rights organizations raised concerns about judicial irregularities throughout the trial. Furthermore, five of the defendants undertook a hunger strike lasting over 30 days.

Unequal land ownership has historically fueled violent conflicts in Paraguay. A 2008 census highlighted this disparity: a mere 2.6% of landowners control 85.5% of the country's land, while 91.4% of small farmers (with holdings under 20 hectares) possess only 6% of agricultural land. Advocates for agrarian reform largely attribute this imbalance to major agricultural conglomerates specializing in soy exports. The Curuguaty incident then served as the catalyst for the opposition Colorado Party to initiate impeachment proceedings against President Lugo, holding him responsible for the fatalities.
Newport Gwent Dragons fly-half Dorian Jones is expected to be out for several months with a chest muscle injury.

The Official Charts Company has confirmed a historic first: an artist simultaneously claimed the top two spots on the charts with newly released tracks. The singer expressed immense satisfaction with this achievement, stating how significant both songs were to him, making their joint ascent to the top particularly remarkable.

Sheeran's return followed a year-long hiatus from social media, dedicated to composing his third album, titled 'Divide.' This period clearly fueled fan anticipation, as the artist subsequently shattered multiple streaming records within a single week. His upbeat pop track, "Shape Of You," proved the more popular, accumulating 13.4 million streams and significantly surpassing Drake's previous record of 8.9 million for "One Dance" last summer. "Castle On The Hill," characterized by its U2-esque guitar riff, also outdid Drake's achievement with 11.07 million streams. Furthermore, on Spotify, Sheeran surpassed One Direction's global streaming record, which was set in August 2015 when "Drag Me Down" garnered 4.76 million streams in a day. "Shape Of You" itself achieved 6.13 million streams on its release Friday, escalating to 7.24 million by Monday.

This exceptional chart dominance by his singles brought an end to Clean Bandit's nine-week reign at number one. Their track, "Rockabye," fell to fourth place, while Rag 'N' Bone Man's "Human" secured the third spot. Other new entries included Sean Paul and Dua Lipa's "No Lie" at 28, and Snakehips' "Don't Leave," featuring Danish artist MÃ, at 33. On the album chart, Little Mix's "Glory Days" maintained its number one position for a fifth consecutive week, making it the most successful album by a girl band since the Spice Girls' 'Spice' held the top spot for 15 weeks in 1996. Elsewhere, David Bowie's "Blackstar" re-entered the top 40 exactly a year following his passing, and his "Legacy" compilation impressively climbed from 18 to number five.
St Johnstone midfielder Murray Davidson will not be risked despite recovering from an ankle fracture.
Through nostalgic black-and-white tones of long-hidden film reels, parts of Northern Ireland's forgotten history are being revealed for the first time.
A remote Orkney island primary school is to lose its only pupil, raising fears about its long-term future.

Most of My Local's stores, specifically 93 out of 125, are set to close. The remaining outlets will stay open while KPMG, the appointed administrator, seeks potential buyers. Should these efforts fail, those stores too will cease operations. The company had a workforce of 1,658 individuals.

Morrisons, a supermarket chain, sold My Local to Greybull Capital last year and has since committed to offering positions to former My Local employees. The retailer found it difficult to compete in the fiercely competitive and price-war-ridden grocery market.

Formerly known as Morrisons' M Local, My Local was acquired by Greybull for Â£25 million. This acquisition was spearheaded by Mike Greene, an experienced figure in retail who gained public recognition from his appearance on Channel 4's The Secret Millionaire.

My Local had indicated earlier this month that administrators were alerted to assume control of the business. Just last week, Morrisons extended a helping hand to My Local's staff, proposing job opportunities within its own supermarkets in the event of store closures.

Mike Greene expressed his regret, stating that the past nine months constituted "one of the toughest retail trading periods" he had ever encountered, with My Local confronting "intense competition." He added that the management team was "unable to return the business to profitability," for which he was "truly sorry."

Mark Orton, a partner at KPMG and joint administrator, commented that the management faced "tough trading conditions," and despite their "best efforts to improve performance," My Local ultimately "was unable to return to viability." He confirmed that while most stores have now ceased operations, KPMG is engaged in "active discussions with a number of interested parties" regarding both the 32 remaining operational premises and a select few that have already shut down.

My Local's collapse highlights a challenging period for the retail industry, coming after the bankruptcies of BHS and Austin Reed. Furthermore, on Tuesday, the owners of Store Twenty One, a fashion retailer, announced plans for a restructuring that could lead to store closures and job cuts.
Scotland's most senior law officer has promised a "thorough, impartial and objective" investigation into the death of Sheku Bayoh.

A cabinet meeting will discuss findings showing 17 temporary staff are paid over Â£500 daily, with two earning more than Â£800. Opposition Conservatives have labelled this spending exorbitant. The Labour-led unitary council defended the outlays, stating specialist expertise was essential for a restructuring program intended to achieve long-term financial savings. Many of these temporary hires, the council explained, provided short-term skills for a project aiming to save Â£30 million by altering how services are delivered. Conservative councillor Ian Bowyer voiced his concern, stating it seemed Plymouth taxpayers were being asked to take "a tremendous leap in the dark" with an outcome that was "far from clear." The council noted it is hiring permanent staff for five of these roles.

During the extensive Thameslink Programme, engineers have unearthed the forgotten ticket hall and platforms of Southwark Park station. This long-vanished station operated briefly from 1902 until its permanent closure in 1915. The Â£6.5 billion Thameslink initiative is a major redevelopment effort, rebuilding railway lines that extend from New Cross Gate through London Bridge to Blackfriars and St Pancras.

Perched on a viaduct above Rotherhithe New Road, Southwark Park was among several local stations, including Spa Road, that ceased operations. Their closures were primarily due to increasing competition from trams and buses, exacerbated by the outbreak of World War One.

The discovery occurred as crews constructed the Bermondsey Dive Under. This project involves the partial demolition and reconstruction of two Victorian viaducts, allowing trains from southeast London and Kent to descend beneath a new route intended for Thameslink services from Croydon.

Project manager Greg Thornett explained: "We found the old platform foundations while preparing the viaduct's upper section for new track. Currently, we're working in the former ticket hall's roof area, sealing existing skylights to accommodate the final track alignment." He added that much of the existing viaduct segment will be replaced by the new dive under's access ramps, but the original arch that housed the booking hall will be preserved.

A Thomson Holidays flight landed at the airport at approximately 3:30 PM BST on Saturday. All passengers disembarked so that comprehensive safety checks could be conducted on the aircraft. Less than two hours later, passengers were cleared to re-board, and the flight subsequently departed at 17:15 BST. According to a Belfast International Airport spokesperson, the flight returned preventatively, as inspections confirmed it had not been struck by lightning.

Welsh international Taylor sustained an injury during Wednesday's training session. Swansea manager Paul Clement confirmed talks are underway to secure the signing of Swedish player Olsson. He stated that both clubs are currently discussing the potential transfer and working to finalize the agreement. Clement indicated that Taylor will 'likely' require three weeks of rehabilitation without physical contact. The Swans' boss also mentioned Taylor will need to be fitted for a protective face mask. Taylor was hospitalized and is scheduled for surgery. Separately, winger Modou Barrow was forced off injured in the 28th minute during Swansea's 2-1 EFL Trophy last-16 victory over Wolves on Tuesday.
The death risk from smoking may be much higher than previously thought - tobacco kills up to two in every three smokers not one in every two, data from a large study suggests.

A collection featuring photographs, medals, and badges is scheduled for auction later this July. According to auctioneer Charles Hanson, this discovery resembles "a time capsule offering fresh insights into the conflict." The photographs were captured by Robert Oliver, a survivor of the 1899-1902 war. Oliver received the Queen's Medal for South Africa, having participated in battles across Cape Colony, the Orange Free State, and the Transvaal during 1901 and 1902. Mr. Hanson noted that these "graphic images depict the brutal reality and genuine horror of war," a stark contrast to what the Victorian press presented, as the British Empire was then considered invincible. Among the photos are prints showing fallen soldiers in fields, the burial service of a British serviceman, and even a Boer War dog. Furthermore, the collection encompasses two original pairs of kid gloves, spurs, an ammunition bandolier, various caps and hats, a genuine South African feathered headdress, and a cartridge belt. Mr. Hanson revealed that "Robert Oliver was quite the renegade in his younger days. At sixteen, he ran off, boarding a ship for Canada where he took up work as a lumberjack." He subsequently joined the Staffordshire Police force, where he earned a reputation for being "amusing yet resolute and disciplined." Additionally, he owned and operated the Devonshire Pub, located in Hartington, Derbyshire. The auction is set for July 25th.

Between September and November, three incidents occurred near the Hillhead Halls of Residence. The suspect is described as a white male, 17-20 years old, approximately 5ft 8in, with short light brown or blond hair. He wore dark sportswear, specifically a hooded top and jogging bottoms.

Detective Constable Kirsty Munro assured the community that officers are treating these reports with utmost seriousness. While the females involved were physically unharmed, they were left understandably concerned and uncomfortable. Uniformed officers are focusing their patrols in the area, and park users are advised to remain vigilant. She added that such incidents are rare both locally and across the city, but urged against complacency. Anyone recognizing the suspect's description or the e-fit image should contact the police.

Early telemetry received after Tuesday's high-speed flyby of the icy dwarf planet (14 km/s or 31,000 mph) confirmed the New Horizons spacecraft remained stable and encountered no problems. This crucial signal was relayed through a large communication antenna located in Madrid, Spain, part of NASA's global network. Traveling across 4.7 billion kilometers of space, the message required four hours and 25 minutes to reach Earth.

Anticipation grew among scientists and engineers at mission control in Laurel, Maryland, as they awaited the vital telemetry. Consequently, immense joy and relief erupted at 01:52 BST when the signal finally arrived, prompting team members to cheer, embrace, and wave American flags in celebration. "We are in lock with telemetry from the spacecraft," announced Alice Bowman, the mission operations manager, upon confirmation of the signal. She added, "We have a healthy spacecraft, we have recorded data from the Pluto system, and we are outbound from Pluto." Minutes later, she conveyed her profound satisfaction, stating, "I can't express how I feel. It's just like we planned it!"

NASA Administrator Charles Bolden remarked that "With this mission, we have visited every single planet in the Solar System," highlighting a significant milestone. John Grunsfeld, the agency's science chief, described the event as "a tremendous moment in human history," further expressing anticipation for the spacecraft's data, which he noted was "full of images and we can't wait."

Alice Bowman, the operations manager, affirmed that New Horizons' solid-state recorder was indeed filled with data. She clarified, "The expected number of segments on that recorder had been used. That tells us that that data has been collected on the spacecraft." The initial signal received Wednesday morning consisted solely of engineering data, intended to verify the successful execution of the flyby sequence. High-resolution images from the encounter were expected to be downlinked later that same day.

Ralph Semmel, director of the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory, the home of mission control, extended congratulations to the entire mission team. He humorously noted Pluto's offerings: "Whales, doughnuts, and a heart," referring to the informal monikers given to surface features visible in images captured during the spacecraft's approach.

Despite the team's confidence in a successful flyby, there remained a slight risk that New Horizons could be lost while traversing the Pluto system at high speed. A collision with even minute icy debris at its velocity of 14 km/s would have proven fatal to the spacecraft. To mark the occasion, James Christy, discoverer of Pluto's moon Charon, and relatives of Clyde Tombaugh, who discovered the dwarf planet in 1930, gathered at mission control to witness the signal's arrival.
Prime Minister Theresa May has held talks with Taoiseach (Irish Prime Minister) Enda Kenny at Downing Street.

A staff member at the Freshway General Store on Rufford Road, Southport, sustained a facial injury and was left "badly shaken" after an armed robbery at approximately 7:30 BST. Merseyside Police confirmed the culprits made off with cash and cigarettes. Officers described both men as wearing dark North Face hooded tops and having green scarves concealing their faces. Detective Inspector Steve Reardon characterized the incident as a "particularly nasty robbery". He emphasized that although the shop assistant was thankfully not seriously hurt while simply carrying out their work, it is crucial to find and bring the perpetrators to justice.

A man and a woman were forcibly removed from their car by a group of men along a highway between Noida, a Delhi suburb, and Kanpur city on Friday, according to reports. Three male relatives accompanying them were assaulted and tied up. The incident has sparked widespread national outrage and raised concerns about police efficiency.

Some victims alleged they received no response from the official helpline number. One male victim informed the Hindustan Times newspaper that the line was continually busy, and when they finally connected, the officer "repeatedly asked questions instead of rescuing the family." Family members also claimed that a police van drove past the field in Bulandshahr where the incident occurred but did not stop.

On Monday, senior police officer Sujeet Pandey told BBC Hindi that three men, arrested on Sunday, were remanded in prison after being identified by their victims. He added that three more men were detained today. The Uttar Pradesh state government has suspended seven police officers in connection with the incident and established a 300-member taskforce to investigate. The family was also robbed of money, jewellery, and their mobile phones.

Scrutiny of sexual violence in India has increased since the 2012 gang rape and murder of a student on a Delhi bus. Nevertheless, brutal sexual attacks against women and children continue to be reported nationwide.

As of Jan 18, 2016: VPNs facilitate secure remote access to company networks. They are, however, often utilized to bypass government censorship or geo-blocking on streaming platforms. BBC Technology reporter Chris Foxx details common VPN applications.

Celebrated annually on March 8th with parades, speeches, and special events, this day emphasizes gender equality. A query asked readers about their inspiring women and reasons. The discussion page is now closed, with thanks for all comments. Sophie, 11, Oxfordshire, is inspired by Rebecca Adlington to become a swimmer. Iona, 9, Northumberland, chose Charlotte Dujardin for her OBE. Nea named her mum and nan.

The memorial spire is an integral part of the International Bomber Command Centre, established to commemorate the over 55,000 personnel who perished during the conflict. Officials reported that while the damage was superficial, it represented a profound lack of respect. It is believed that the vandals utilized breeze blocks from the site itself in an attempt to scale the inside of the monument.

Nicky Barr, the centre's director, observed that the perpetrators had likely cut through a perimeter fence, with scuff marks inside the memorial probably caused by the falling blocks. She expressed immense disappointment, stating, "It is hugely disappointing that a memorial this county has worked so hard for, that honours the dead of Bomber Command, has been subjected to this kind of abject vandalism." She also conveyed the immense pride felt for the spire, which locals affectionately call 'our memorial', highlighting the significant effort invested despite its recent construction just a year ago. Barr reiterated the act as a clear sign of disrespect. Furthermore, she warned that anyone attempting to climb the approximately 30-meter high structure, with its paved base, would be putting themselves "at real risk of injury," potentially leading to severe harm and being left stranded.

The spire was officially unveiled in October, with approximately 300 Bomber Command veterans in attendance. During World War Two, 125,000 aircrew served in Bomber Command, undertaking 364,514 operational sorties. Of these, a tragic 55,573 aircrew lost their lives, including 25,611 originating from Lincolnshire. Overall, 70% of aircrew were either killed, taken prisoner, or injured.

On Friday at approximately 8:05 PM, violent attacks occurred in Castlemilk, Glasgow. Police reported that a boy was seriously assaulted while walking in Ardencraig Quadrant, close to its intersection with Ardencraig Drive. His 52-year-old father, who witnessed the incident, was also attacked when he tried to intervene. Both father and son sustained facial injuries and were treated in hospital before being discharged. The two assailants were described as white males, aged between 17 and 21, and wearing dark clothing. Detective Constable Peter McFarlane stated these were "violent and unprovoked" attacks, and officers are conducting door-to-door inquiries and reviewing surveillance footage to identify those responsible. Despite believing the incident was random, additional patrols will be deployed to reassure the public.

In a separate incident, a 23-year-old man was assaulted in Partick around 8:00 PM on Saturday, in what police suspect was a targeted attack. The victim was walking along Exeter Drive, near its junction with Dumbarton Road, when a man exited a passing grey BMW 3 Series saloon, seriously attacked him, then re-entered the car and drove away.
