Bystanders assisted the injured man, who was hospitalized for head and facial injuries before being released. Police did not provide a description of the suspect but noted his vehicle. Detective Constable David Hardie confirmed they believe this was a targeted assault, with officers currently investigating the area and checking CCTV to gather more information on the circumstances and the perpetrator. Detectives are appealing for anyone with details regarding either assault to come forward.
Justice Secretary Chris Grayling has dismissed reports the government is planning to allow nude weddings.
An Â¬Â£8m transformation of public spaces at the University of Sheffield has started.

Paul Newall, 30, from Larkhall, died in a fatal motorcycle accident on Thursday at approximately 10:40 PM. His Kawasaki bike collided with a white Mazda 2 on the M74 southbound carriageway, near Junction 7, Larkhall. The 43-year-old woman driving the car was not injured. Both vehicles were travelling in the same direction before the impact. Sgt Billy Broatch of Police Scotland is urging witnesses to come forward, specifically those who saw the crash or the motorcyclist travelling with another motorbike on the M74 shortly beforehand.

Zee Entertainment Enterprises has announced plans to dub its entire catalog of Bollywood films, originally recorded in Hindi, into Spanish. This new channel, Zee Mundo, represents the company's first foray into marketing Indian cinema to the Hispanic audience. The firm also aims to expand its presence to include Mexico, Argentina, Colombia, Peru, and Chile. Bollywood movies, characterized by their elaborate action sequences, song-and-dance numbers, and vibrant costumes, have previously achieved success in non-Hindi speaking territories such as Nigeria, China, and various parts of Latin America. The company believes there are cultural commonalities between the Spanish-speaking market and India, anticipating that Bollywood content will appeal to viewers familiar with Spanish-language soap operas. Promotional materials indicate the channel will be offered in high definition, alongside a complimentary on-demand streaming service. Amit Goenka, head of the company's international division, stated, "We are confident that Zee Mundo's programming will cross frontiers with storylines and themes that are relatable to the Hispanic audiences." Zee Entertainment Enterprises, counted among India's largest media conglomerates, asserts a global reach of over one billion viewers.
Chris Venables gave Bala Town a lifeline in their Europa League first qualifying round tie against FC Vaduz.

A teenager faces charges for drug distribution in East Calder, where authorities are investigating the death of 15-year-old Dione Melville. Emergency services responded to a residence in the town on Sunday morning, but tragically, Dione was pronounced deceased a short while later. Investigators currently classify the death as "unexplained." As a precautionary measure, two other 15-year-old girls were transported to St John's Hospital in Livingston.

Dione was a student at West Calder High School. Acting head teacher Lisa Grubb stated that Dione was a popular girl, and this period is understandably distressing for her loved ones and friends. Ms. Grubb added that Dione was an ambitious young woman with aspirations of pursuing a career in hairdressing and the beauty sector upon graduating this summer. She was highly focused on her future, and the entire school community extends its deepest sympathies to Dione's family and friends during this profoundly sorrowful period.

Many tributes have appeared on social media, posted by her friends. One such message read: "Rest in paradise, my beautiful girl. You didn't deserve to be taken from us. Shine bright, fly high and sleep tight babe. I love and miss you forever and ever my girl."

Private Sean Benton was discovered deceased at the Deepcut barracks in Surrey in June 1995, having sustained five gunshot wounds while on guard duty at a perimeter fence. The human rights group Liberty stated that the Attorney General has granted his family permission to apply to the High Court, despite an earlier inquest having recorded a suicide verdict for the 20-year-old soldier.

Earlier this month, a second inquest, examining the death of Private Cheryl James â who also died at Deepcut in 1995 from a single gunshot wound â similarly returned a suicide verdict. Over 100 witnesses testified during the Cheryl James inquiry. In his ruling, Coroner Brian Barker QC strongly criticized Deepcut's welfare provisions, citing compelling evidence of a pervasive sexualized environment.

Representing Pte Benton's twin brother Tony and his sister Tracy Lewis, Liberty submitted an application to the Attorney General in July 2015, seeking to nullify the initial July 1995 inquest and demand a new investigation. Liberty stated that since Pte Benton's death, numerous individuals have informed his family and publicly asserted their belief that he, originally from Hastings, East Sussex, endured physical and psychological bullying at the barracks.

Ms Lewis expressed being "overwhelmed and disturbed by all the details of the shameful environment at Deepcut which have finally come to light through the Cheryl James inquest â it is terrible to think of Sean alone there." She added that over two decades after their brother's passing, and having recently lost both parents, she and Tony are "determined to find out what happened to Sean."

Pte Benton was the initial casualty among four young recruits who succumbed to gunshot wounds at Deepcut between 1995 and 2002. Liberty highlighted that the first inquest, held merely a month after his death, involved testimony from only six individuals. Crucially, Pte Benton's medical and mental health records were not procured, nor was any evidence gathered or presented regarding his experiences at the barracks. Emma Norton, a lawyer for Liberty, asserted that a proper and independent investigation into Pte Benton's death in 1995 could have spared his family decades of suffering and unresolved questions.

In 2014, 66-year-old James Percival claimed he administered mouth-to-mouth resuscitation to infant Jonathan Percival at the Freckleton vicarage in Lancashire. However, 30-year-old Ruth Percival stated she witnessed no such efforts to revive the child. The inquest was previously suspended in October after fresh medical findings prompted the coroner to refer the matter to prosecuting authorities. By March, the Crown Prosecution Service had concluded there was "insufficient evidence" to bring charges against any individual.

During the Blackpool Town Hall hearing, it was revealed that Miss Percival, who has special educational needs, sought a pregnancy termination at her GP surgery in August 2014. However, the procedure could not be performed as her pregnancy was too advanced. She admitted to having avoided confronting her pregnancy and to having concealed it from her parents due to fear of their response.

Mr. Percival, then the vicar of Holy Trinity CE Church in Freckleton, recounted that on the afternoon of November 25, upon her return from work, she spent time in the downstairs restroom. He described seeing her emerge from the bathroom around 3:30 PM GMT, carrying a towel he thought was soiled with excrement. They went outside to dispose of it when, he stated, "Jonathan's leg came into view." He testified in court, recalling his words to Ruth: "This is a baby, you can't put a baby in the bin." He then stated he laid the infant on the towel on the ground outside and tried to revive him. He described the baby as "extremely cold, completely lifeless," concluding, "The baby was clearly deceased."

Medical evidence presented at the inquest indicated the baby was alive at birth. Miss Percival testified that she believed she saw the baby attempt to breathe, yet also stated, "I somehow thought I had a miscarriage because, to me, the baby was dead when it emerged from me." Both Miss Percival and her father provided testimony indicating Jonathan's umbilical cord was wrapped around his neck. The hearing is scheduled to resume on Tuesday.

The National Environment Research Council (NERC) affirmed its decision to conduct a public poll for naming a new vessel, a process in which "Boaty McBoatface" received the most votes. Professor Duncan Wingham stated that the controversy surrounding the name had "put a smile" on people's faces. However, Members of Parliament questioned if ministers, who ultimately named the ship after Sir David Attenborough, would consequently punish Professor Wingham.

Wingham was providing testimony to the Commons Science and Technology Committee regarding this highly publicized event, which generated immense public interest and divided opinion after "Boaty McBoatface" was overlooked for the main ship. He characterized the ministers' resolution to christen the primary vessel after the renowned zoologist and broadcaster â an option that ranked fourth in the survey â while also assigning "Boaty McBoatface" to a remotely operated sub-sea vehicle, as an "eloquent compromise."

When Conservative MP Nicola Blackwood asked about the episode's impact on public engagement in science, Wingham, an academic, asserted that the "extraordinary attention" it garnered could only be seen as an "incredible success." He proclaimed that NERC could now "make the claim that we are probably the best-known research council in the world." He further added that, as a result, "hundreds of thousands of people, not only in the UK but around the world," now know about NERC and its scientific work. Wingham concluded, "In many ways we feel this has been an astonishingly great outcome for us. In addition, it has put a smile on everyone's face." Professor Wingham indicated that NERC would repeat a similar public naming process in the future, though no current plans for other boats exist.

Lions coach Warren Gatland has dismissed efforts by Richard Cockerill, Toulon's coach, to secure fullback Leigh Halfpenny's participation in the Top 14 final on June 4, should his French club advance to the championship match. Gatland firmly stated that Halfpenny's schedule is predetermined and he will join the Lions squad at the tour's outset. He confirmed speaking with Leigh, who is scheduled for a week off before his club's quarter-final on May 19, followed by a potential semi-final. Gatland reiterated that Halfpenny will be involved in any semi-final Toulon plays, but will then immediately link up with the Lions, just like all other selected players, thereby ruling out his presence in the final.

Additionally, Gatland provided an optimistic assessment regarding the fitness of tour captain Sam Warburton, who is currently recovering from a knee injury. There is a possibility Warburton could participate for the Cardiff Blues in their European Champions Cup play-offs before the Lions' departure. However, Gatland clarified that the decision regarding his immediate return to play rests collectively with Warburton himself, his clubs, and the medical team. While Sam informed Gatland last week that he felt capable of playing "at a push," Gatland stressed the importance of not jeopardizing his recovery by pushing him too soon. He prefers Warburton to have an additional couple of weeks, potentially for more conditioning work, ensuring he is fully prepared and integrated for the tour's commencement.
Three men have been arrested on suspicion of murder after a man was found dead on Christmas Eve.

Two charities, Mencap and the Challenging Behaviour Foundation, have highlighted the dangers associated with relocating patients great distances from their homes. This caution coincides with the imminent release of findings from a serious case review concerning patient abuse at a private facility located close to Bristol. The BBC Panorama programme brought this abuse to light through covert filming. Eleven individuals have pleaded guilty to charges of neglect and mistreatment linked to the incidents. The South Gloucestershire Safeguarding Adults Board (SAB) commissioned an independent expert to conduct this review.

Since the Panorama broadcast in May of the previous year, Mencap and the Challenging Behaviour Foundation have received 260 reports from families detailing abuse and neglect within institutional care settings. Their collaborative report, titled 'Out of Sight', documented numerous severe incidents reported by families, encompassing physical and sexual assault, along with excessive use of restraint.

Mark Goldring, Mencap's chief executive, expressed concern, stating that without a robust government plan to shut down large care facilities and establish suitable local services for individuals with learning disabilities, another scandal akin to Winterbourne View is highly probable. The charities indicated that hundreds of people with learning disabilities are presently housed in assessment and treatment units similar to Winterbourne View. They highlighted that many of these facilities are situated far from patients' homes, increasing their vulnerability to neglect and abuse.

Vivien Cooper, who founded the Challenging Behaviour Foundation, voiced profound worries regarding patient safety and well-being. She elaborated that "hundreds of individuals with learning disabilities are being placed in distant care institutions, often for years unnecessarily, leaving them susceptible to neglect and abuse."

A spokesperson for the Department of Health affirmed their stance: individuals should, whenever feasible, receive support to reside in their own homes within their local communities. While acknowledging that a limited number of cases may necessitate high-quality assessment and treatment services, potentially involving brief inpatient stays, they stressed that this should not replace excellent community-based care. The spokesperson underlined the critical importance of properly commissioning and regularly reviewing all services, ensuring they are not employed as permanent solutions.

Subsequent to the BBC investigation, twenty-four patients were moved from the Castlebeck-operated Winterbourne View hospital, located near Hambrook. The facility closed the subsequent month. The criminal charges specifically pertained to five patients from the hospital, and all those charged are currently awaiting their sentences.

The 26-year-old athlete was excluded from the team, despite having achieved the Olympic qualifying time six times and finishing third in the trials. Writing on eightlane.org, she expressed her understanding that she would "never secure an Olympic medal."

When asked for a statement, UK Athletics declared they do not comment on individual athlete selection policies. For the Rio squad, only Shelayna Oskan-Clarke and Lynsey Sharp were named as 800m runners for Team GB, leaving a third position vacant.

Leonard criticized this decision, stating that "leaving an empty slot on an Olympic team when numerous athletes meet the qualifying standard is an insult to the dedication athletes put into their sport." She elaborated that it suggests "the demanding early starts, cold runs, hill training, missed social events, and every other sacrifice we make are pointless unless one reaches the Olympic final."

She further admitted that being told the spot would remain unfilled despite her third-place finish in the trials made her feel "unexceptional."

Last month, at the British Championships, the Chorley runner completed her race in 2 minutes 2.45 seconds, behind Oskan-Clarke and Sharp. However, she conveyed that the selection outcome had left her feeling like a "minor competitor." She concluded by likening herself to "an extra on the stage of athletics, where no one cares that I diligently rehearsed; I am not needed, and my segment has been cut."

Hawick launched the Borders' common riding season on Friday with the appearance of horses. The 2017 Cornet, Ali George, and his Lass, Katy Moffat, guided the procession through the town. Hawick is one of several Borders communities that host these annual summer celebrations. A key part of the ceremony involves a horseback group circling the town's historic boundaries.

Portland's Fancy's Farm is requesting discarded trees to feed its 25-strong herd of various goats. The goats strip the trees' greenery, and the bare branches are then repurposed as natural habitats on the farm. Manager Sue Illsley stated, "They adore them; the roughage in the needles offers significant health benefits."

A yellow "be aware" warning was issued by the Met Office at 08:45, covering the Highlands, parts of Aberdeenshire, and central Scotland due to prevailing weather conditions. This alert specified ice and snow accumulations of approximately one inch (4cm) on terrain above 656ft (200m), increasing to three inches (10cm) at elevations above 1,312ft (400m), and remains valid until 23:00. Key routes impacted included the A82 at Altnafeadh and the A9 at Drumochter.

The Met Office advised the public to "be aware" of potentially challenging driving conditions throughout the day, which could lead to localised transport disruption. They explained that a cold, showery westerly airflow was expected across Scotland, with low-pressure troughs delivering extensive and heavy wintry showers. While snow was predicted mainly for higher elevations, more intense showers might occasionally bring it down to lower levels.

Among the areas experiencing significant snowfall was the Cairngorms region. Notably, the Highland Wildlife Park, situated in Kincraig near Aviemore, is home to three polar bears: two males named Arktos and Walker, and a female called Victoria. Earlier on Friday, park staff and visitors celebrated the bears' birthdays with special frozen treats.

Afghanistan's intelligence service attributed a recent Wednesday attack to militants allegedly supported by Islamabad. The Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) subsequently stated its unwillingness to play against "a country where terrorists are housed and provided safe havens." The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) retaliated by accusing the ACB of "playing politics." Pakistan, for its part, denied any involvement in the capital's attack, refuting the Afghan claims.

In a statement, the PCB strongly rejected what it called the "baseless allegations levelled by Afghanistan Cricket Board" in the wake of the tragic Kabul blast. While expressing sympathy for the victims, the PCB deemed the ACB's statement "irresponsible" and announced the cancellation of the proposed series between the two nations. The PCB clarified that an informal understanding reached last weekend was contingent upon conducive security conditions in Afghanistan, which are now absent due to "continuing insecurity and instability there," thus nullifying the agreement.

The bomb killed at least 90 people in Kabul, the city where a Twenty20 match was provisionally scheduled for later this year, intended to be followed by a fixture in Pakistan and then a full series at an unconfirmed date. Despite this, the ACB's statement explicitly declared a cancellation of "all kinds of cricket matches and initial mutual relationship agreement with the Pakistan Cricket Board."

Historically, Pakistan contributed to the growth of cricket in Afghanistan, supplying equipment and organizing matches. However, in 2016, Afghanistan's national team shifted its home base from Sharjah in the United Arab Emirates to Noida, Delhi. Concurrently, India's former batsman Lalchand Rajput replaced Pakistan's Inzamam-ul-Haq as their national team coach.

Pakistan has faced significant touring challenges; only Zimbabwe has visited the country for a cricket series since a 2009 militant attack on the touring Sri Lanka team. Furthermore, India has refused to play a full series against Pakistan since the 2008 Mumbai attacks, and relations with Bangladesh worsened after Pakistan withdrew from a series scheduled there for July.
Exeter flanker Julian Salvi has been ruled out for the rest of 2016 after injuring his biceps.

Facing a decline in demand and escalating expenses, the company has "temporarily halted" operations at its Redcar blast furnace. SSI, which took over the previously mothballed Tata Steel site in 2010, employs almost 2,000 individuals there.

According to Ms. Soubry, European Union regulations restrict the government's ability to directly provide financial aid to British steel manufacturers. Cornelius Louwrens, SSI's chief operating officer, pressed the government to "take concrete action, not just offer words," to help ensure the plant's survival. He emphasized that "other nations in Europe are actively supporting their steel sectors because they recognize its critical importance."

He requested ministers to endorse the backing of "essential projects," which would enable SSI to obtain commercial credit, alongside reducing corporate taxes and loosening regulations related to carbon dioxide emissions.

However, Ms. Soubry reiterated that "exceptionally stringent state aid rules, particularly affecting the steel industry, limit our options." She clarified that while "funding for initiatives like research and development is permissible, providing direct loans or underwriting is not." She acknowledged the "extremely challenging circumstances at SSI," but maintained that the government's "hands are tied." Despite this, she stated they "will continue to collaborate with the company and trade unions," identifying global steel overproduction as the fundamental problem. She added that "the Prime Minister views this as a crucial British industry, and the government remains committed to offering all possible support."

Union representatives at the facility called the company's choice "catastrophic" and have requested immediate discussions with management.

Queen's Lodge in Colwyn Bay, originally the residence of the first Lord Colwyn, was converted into two care facilities after the 1946 death of industrialist and banker, Frederick Henry Smith. The estate's extensive grounds boasted a lake, a croquet lawn, a bowling green, and prize-winning gardens. The final sale price remains undisclosed. Records from the National Monuments Record of Wales indicate it was acquired in 1946 by the former Merseyside Hospitals Council, a health insurance program. Individuals from Merseyside utilized the property for recuperation, often sending postcards featuring images of the main house and its surroundings to their families and friends. Queen's Lodge was renamed the John Braddock Convalescent Home, while the Mary Bamber Convalescent Centre was constructed within its premises. The Colwyn Bay Heritage Group highlighted Queen's Lodge as a significant structure, having been the ancestral home of Lord Colwyn and his family, who were renowned as "great benefactors of the town." Agents Legat Owen commented that the entire site presented potential for diverse applications.

A victory this Saturday could bring former WBA super-bantamweight champion Scott Quigg closer to a bout with Welsh fighter Lee Selby. Quigg's promoter, Eddie Hearn, emphasized, "It's a great opportunity for Scott." He added that with "uncertainty over [Selby's mandatory challenger] Jonathan Barros, it's very likely the winner will fight Lee Selby next." Quigg moved up to featherweight after his only career loss in 35 fights â a unification bout where he forfeited his WBA title to Carl Frampton in February 2016. The 28-year-old is competing for the first time since enlisting American Freddie Roach as his trainer. Since his defeat by Carl Frampton last February, Quigg has fought and won only once, leading to a dip in his public profile, while those of rivals Selby and Frampton have ascended. His clash with the 35-year-old Simion is featured on the undercard of Anthony Joshua's IBF and WBA heavyweight title showdown against Wladimir Klitschko.
Carlisle United have confirmed that Derek Asamoah has agreed a short-term deal following a recent trial spell.

Campaign group Liberty asserts that the extensive collection of electronic data by intelligence agencies, facilitated by certain powers, constitutes an "assault on our freedom." The Investigatory Powers Act (IPA), which grants these powers, received royal assent in November. The government has pledged to uphold this legislation.

Under the IPA, state agencies are authorized to control and alter electronic devices, access private communications like texts, online messages, and emails, and monitor phone calls, even without any suspicion of criminal activity. The act requires telecommunication firms to store metadataâincluding sender, location, and timeâfor calls, emails, texts, and web browsing, but explicitly not the content itself.

Liberty, however, seeks to legally contest the legitimacy of these powers and is publicly fundraising for a judicial review. Liberty director Martha Spurrier states that the government, last year, "exploited fear and distraction to quietly create the most extreme surveillance regime of any democracy in history." She added that "hundreds of thousands" have since called for its repeal, deeming it an "unprecedented, unjustified assault on our freedom." In November 2016, a petition advocating the act's repeal garnered over 118,000 signatures.

The Investigatory Powers Act, proposed by then-Home Secretary Theresa May, was approved by the House of Lords on November 19. Though the act's "bulk powers" are highly contentious, security services and the government maintain they are vital for counter-terrorism. Last month, demands arose for the government to revise the act after the European Court of Justice ruled "general and indiscriminate" retention of communications data unlawful. EU judges stipulated such data could only be retained for serious crime investigations. BBC legal correspondent Clive Coleman noted the government's strong commitment to defending the act, asserting it protects both privacy and security, received unprecedented parliamentary scrutiny, and secured cross-party support.

The 26-year-old, boasting over 160 career appearances, previously featured as a midfielder for SC Amiens, Rayo Vallecano, and Dijon, and can also cover centre-back. MK boss Robbie Neilson told the League One club's website that a reliable French contact recommended the player, whom they'd thoroughly scouted. Neilson expects him to "bring physicality and strength to the middle of the pitch." For all the latest football transfers, visit our dedicated page.

Thomas Groome, aged 53, vanished on New Year's Day 2010, after being last seen by his family in Thorne, Doncaster. Following a five-week trial, Jason Thaxter, from Hexthorpe, Doncaster, was found guilty of murder and conspiracy to prevent a burial. He received a sentence of at least 30 years in prison, handed down at Sheffield Crown Court. Although initially investigated as a missing person's case, a murder inquiry into Mr Groome's disappearance began in 2012. Thaxter, then 39, and his mother, June Buttle, were first apprehended in 2013. Buttle was charged the subsequent year; however, there was insufficient evidence to charge her son at that point. In 2015, the 57-year-old Doncaster resident received a 16-year sentence after admitting guilt to charges of manslaughter, conspiracy to prevent a burial, and fraud. Temp Det Ch Supt Lisa Ray of South Yorkshire Police expressed hope that both individuals would "do the decent thing" by revealing the location of Mr Groome's body to his family. In a statement, his family described him as a "larger-than-life character" with a passion for travel. They recounted saying goodbye on January 1, 2010, unaware it would be their final encounter. His relatives expressed devastation at being unable to lay him to rest in a place they could visit and remember him, preventing them from giving him the funeral he deserved.

Profits at the tech titan increased by 17% compared to the same period last year. CEO Steve Ballmer stated that their "devices and services transformation" was progressing well, adding that a "wide range" of new products would be launched in the upcoming quarter. The report, however, offered no new details regarding Ballmer's successor, as he had previously announced plans to retire within the next year.

This quarter, the company released several new offerings, including an update to Windows 8, and recently completed the acquisition of struggling Finnish giant Nokia's mobile phone unit. Bolstered by the strong results, shares climbed 6% in after-hours trading.

Microsoft also disclosed sales figures for its tablet computer, Surface, for the first time. Revenues from Surface reached $400 million, showing sequential growth in both revenue and units sold compared to the previous quarter. This positive news follows a challenging last quarter, where the company incurred an embarrassing $900 million write-down due to sluggish sales of the device. Despite being well-regarded by reviewers and marking Microsoft's initial venture into hardware manufacturing, many consumers, already expressing dissatisfaction with Microsoft's Windows operating system update, did not embrace it. The company still withheld exact sales figures for the device.

Investors hoping for information about Ballmer's replacement in the new year were left disappointed. Earlier today, during an an earnings conference call, Ford CEO Alan Mulally declined to comment on rumors that he was being considered for the top executive role. Other potential candidates include Stephen Elop, former head of Nokia, who resigned after Microsoft announced its September plan to purchase Nokia's mobile phone division for 5.4 billion euros ($7.2 billion; Â£4.6 billion). Mr. Elop currently leads Devices and Services at Nokia, but is expected to transition to Microsoft, where he previously held a senior management position, once the deal concludes. Ballmer has served as Microsoft's CEO since 2000 and has been with the company since 1980.
Australia and Papua New Guinea will hold urgent talks next week over the fate of asylum seekers held at a detention centre on Manus Island.

Detailed terms of the agreement reveal that GM has, in fact, incurred a substantial loss of up to Â£6 billion to divest itself of Vauxhall and Opel.

Firstly, a significant portion of the sale price â three-quarters of a billion pounds â is allocated not for manufacturing plants, but for loans taken out by Opel and Vauxhall car owners through GM's financial services division. Peugeot is acquiring these outstanding loans at eighty percent of their book value.

Secondly, GM will retain the majority of the existing pension liabilities. Peugeot will assume responsibility for a few specific schemes, for which GM is paying them Â£2.6 billion as an agreement fee.

Thirdly, the Detroit-based automotive giant will record an accounting impairment of Â£3.2 billion on the transaction. This confirms that the valuation it previously held for Opel and Vauxhall in its own financial records was largely driven by optimism and the scale of past investments, rather than concrete expectations of future profits.

However, GM's financial outlay does not imply that Vauxhall and Opel are destined not to succeed under their new owner. Peugeot anticipates generating Â£1.5 billion in cost savings from the integrated operations, and should the deal help the French automaker penetrate new markets, it will have served its purpose.

Meanwhile, GM continues to scale back its global ambitions and sharpen its strategic focus. Since receiving a bailout from the US government following the financial crisis, it has discontinued American brands such as Oldsmobile, Saturn, Hummer, and Pontiac, and divested its Australian plants, which had produced cars since 1931.

This strategic retraction might be perceived as a departure from former prominence, but it could also reflect GM's pragmatic conviction that its future lies in China â where it is the most robust US competitor â and in electric and self-driving vehicles, sectors where America, not Europe, holds a leadership position.

David Craig Ellis, 41, has confessed to causing the death of 59-year-old Alec Warburton at a Swansea residence, but pleaded not guilty to murder. Mr. Warburton's body was found in a disused north Wales quarry over a month after he vanished. The two-week trial at Swansea Crown Court heard claims Ellis "lost control" following a request for sexual favours. Jurors began deliberations on Monday afternoon.
Labour donor John Mills has quit the cross-party Vote Leave campaign saying he wanted to concentrate on making his party's case for Brexit.
A killer confessed to his housemate's murder during a tarot card reading as the devil card was dealt.

A notable market downturn impacted US stocks, largely offsetting the gains made by the financial and energy sectors. The Nasdaq Composite, heavily weighted with technology firms, dropped 113.84 points (1.80%) to close at 6,207.92. Meanwhile, the broader S&P 500 saw a modest decline of 2.02 points (0.08%), ending at 2,431.77, while the Dow Jones Industrial Average managed to climb 89.44 points (0.42%) to reach 21,271.97.

Earlier in the week, US markets had shown limited movement, as investors awaited the outcomes of the UK general election and the implications of former FBI Director James Comey's testimony in Washington. President Trump's decision to dismiss Mr. Comey, who was overseeing the FBI's investigation into alleged connections between Russia and the Trump campaign, sparked political controversy, potentially jeopardizing significant business policies in Washington. However, Comey's testimony offered minimal fresh disclosures, and Republicans seemed confident in their ability to advance core legislative agendas, including the deregulation of financial markets.

On Friday, financial sector shares climbed by almost 2%, and energy stocks saw gains of over 2% amidst stabilizing oil prices. Nevertheless, these positive movements were insufficient to counteract the decline experienced by technology equities. Major tech companies saw significant drops: Netflix declined 4.7%, Apple fell 3.9%, Alphabet (Google's parent company) dropped 3.4%, Facebook was down 3.3%, and Amazon lost 3.2%. The prolonged success of these companies on Wall Street had earned them the acronym FAANG and fueled ongoing discussions about their potentially overvalued shares; however, the precise catalyst for the extensive sell-off remained unclear.

Despite this, not all internet-based firms suffered declines. Pandora's stock, for instance, surged 1.2% on Friday following the music streaming service's announcement of a $480 million cash injection from Sirius XM. Pandora stated that this investment from the satellite radio provider, Sirius XM, would provide the necessary capital for its expansion, while also offering Sirius XM exposure to the burgeoning online radio market.

On Monday, police responded to a house break-in in the city's Shiregreen area. The victim is hospitalized with gunshot injuries, in a serious and potentially life-threatening condition. Two men, aged 24 and 25, have been arrested and remain in custody on suspicion of aggravated burglary. South Yorkshire Police described it as an isolated incident. Det Insp Paul Wilson stated that several lines of inquiry are being pursued. He reassured the public that despite being alarming, such incidents are rare, and all available resources are dedicated to investigating and identifying those accountable.

Andreea Cristea tragically passed away, becoming the fifth victim of the March 22nd attack, in which Khalid Masood drove a vehicle into pedestrians on Westminster Bridge, then fatally stabbed a police officer, before being shot dead himself. The 31-year-old, who was on holiday with her boyfriend, Andrei Burnaz, had remained hospitalized since the incident. It later came to light that Mr. Burnaz had planned to propose to her on their outing.

Her family, in a statement, confirmed the architect's death on Thursday. They shared their profound grief, stating that after a two-week struggle for survival, their "beloved and irreplaceable Andreea â wonderful daughter, sister, partner, dedicated friend and the most unique and life loving person you can imagine â was cruelly and brutally ripped away from our lives in the most heartless and spiritless way." They added, "She will always be remembered as our shining ray of light that will forever keep on shining in our hearts."

The family also expressed immense gratitude to the medical team for their "never-ending dedication," stating they were "deeply touched and eternally grateful" and that their "kindness and empathy are beyond compare." They concluded by saying, "There are no words to even begin to describe the crushing pain and emptiness that is left in our hearts."

Mr. Burnaz, who himself sustained a broken foot during the assault, recently returned to Westminster Bridge to place a single white rose in remembrance. According to Romania's UK ambassador, Dan Mihalache, who spoke to the BBC, the couple were in London for Mr. Burnaz's birthday, and he had intended to propose. Mihalache further explained that it is believed Masood's vehicle struck Mr. Burnaz after mounting the pavement, subsequently forcing Ms. Cristea into the River Thames.

London Mayor Sadiq Khan conveyed his deep sorrow over Andreea Cristea's passing, tweeting that "Londoners hold her & her loved ones in our thoughts today."

The attack also claimed the lives of Aysha Frade, 44, a London sixth-form college employee; US tourist Kurt Cochran, 54, from Utah; and Leslie Rhodes, 75, a retired window cleaner from south London. Additionally, PC Keith Palmer, a father of two, was fatally stabbed outside Parliament.

A "service of hope" was held at Westminster Abbey on Wednesday, where relatives of the victims were joined by members of the Royal Family. Ms. Cristea's family has requested that funds initially donated for her recovery now be redirected to charity.

British world heavyweight boxing champion, Tyson Fury, issued an apology last month for a video shared online that featured homophobic, sexist, and anti-Semitic remarks. His upcoming opponent, former champion Klitschko, who is set to face Fury in Manchester on July 9, expressed his dismay, stating: "I was stunned by his comments. When he spoke about Jewish people, he sounded like Hitler. The man is an imbecile." The 40-year-old Ukrainian, who suffered his first defeat in 11 years to Fury last November, added: "We cannot have a champion like him. He either needs to be silenced, defeated in the ring, or suspended, because we mustn't allow more hatred to be spread. I am fighting someone who struggles to control what he says." The Campaign Against Antisemitism has also demanded a ban for Fury and lodged a complaint with the British Boxing Board of Control. Fury, the undefeated 27-year-old who captured the WBA and WBO heavyweight belts from Klitschko in their initial encounter, later expressed regret for causing offense and pledged to improve his behaviour "as an ambassador of British boxing." He also faced backlash following his victory over Klitschko last year, when remarks concerning homosexuality, paedophilia, and women prompted over 100,000 individuals to sign an online petition requesting his removal from the BBC's 2015 Sports Personality of the Year shortlist.

At the close of day three, the visiting team had reached 293 for 9, establishing a lead of 260 runs. Jacques Rudolph's pursuit of his inaugural Championship century in 2016 was prolonged when he was dismissed for 56, hitting the ball onto his own stumps. Previously, Essex had been dismissed for 319, with Craig Meschede achieving his first five-wicket haul of the Championship season, ending with figures of 5 for 84. The host team confirmed their promotion and clinched the second-tier title by surpassing 250 runs in their first innings, primarily due to captain Ryan ten Doeschate's century; he contributed an additional eight runs to his overnight total before being out for 117. As a bowler, Ten Doeschate (2 for 20) dismissed both Rudolph and Bragg (54) in his opening over. Bragg had just crossed 1,000 Championship runs for the season, and the duo had earlier formed an 89-run partnership for the second wicket. Although Glamorgan suffered a collapse, losing six wickets for only 36 runs, Mark Wallace (75 not out) and Timm van der Gugten (32) played crucial roles in extending their lead beyond 250. Glamorgan batsman Will Bragg commented to BBC Wales Sport: "A four-day match can fluctuate significantly, but Wally (Mark Wallace) displayed tremendous resilience, placing us in a strong competitive position for the final day. Maintaining consistency throughout a lengthy season is challenging, so reaching 1,000 runs is gratifying. I find my batting to be more consistent when positioned at number three. I am pleased with how I've avoided throwing my wicket away frequently this year. While the team's performance has been disappointing, there are encouraging indications with emerging young talent, providing much to build on for the future."

Logan Murdoch was critically injured and unresponsive when the Great North Air Ambulance team arrived at the scene of the 2016 collision at Newby Cross. Hayley Murdoch, 29, and Sheila Dixon, 71, both from Carlisle, tragically died in the crash. Despite the severity of his condition, Logan, later dubbed a "ray of sunshine" by Dr Laura Duffy after his full recovery, suffered an "internal decapitation"âa separation of the spinal column from the skull's baseâin addition to brain injuries, a punctured lung, and a broken collar bone. Dr Duffy noted that his survival seemed improbable given the extent of his injuries. The young boy was resuscitated roadside and subsequently placed into a medically-induced coma at the scene. He also received blood transfusions en route to the hospital, eventually making a complete recovery. Loganâs father, John Murdoch, shared that his son's neurosurgeon deemed Logan's case extremely rare. In 25 years as a neurosurgeon, he had only encountered two other patients alive after an "internal decapitation"; one subsequently died, and the other was left severely paralysed, underscoring Logan's extraordinary luck. John affirmed that GNAAS saved Loganâs life. Later, Logan, his father, and grandmother Karen Rooney visited the air ambulance base to meet Dr Laura Duffy and paramedic Colin Clark, who had attended the crash.

Stefan Appleton, an 18-year-old, was fatally attacked while with friends in Islington's Nightingale Park on June 10 of the previous year. The Old Bailey trial revealed that the assailant, having dismounted a stolen moped, stabbed Appleton with a 25-inch (63cm) serrated knife. The 17-year-old attacker, whose identity is protected by law due to his age, was acquitted of murder but is scheduled for sentencing on April 21. Jurors heard that Appleton, an Islington college student, was with companions when his attacker dismounted a scooter, produced the weapon, and pursued the group. After tripping and falling, Appleton was repeatedly stabbed. Police confirmed his death resulted from shock and haemorrhage caused by a chest stab wound. The Metropolitan Police has since issued warnings about 'zombie' knives, noting how these decorative blades are being marketed. The force also highlighted that children were present and playing in the park during the incident. As the killer was driven away from the scene, the court was told he yelled "RP," short for Red Pitch, signifying a rival gang to one in Nightingale Park. The 17-year-old alleged getaway driver was also acquitted of murder, and another 17-year-old boy was found not guilty of conspiring to inflict grievous bodily harm. Following the machete attack, the assailant escaped to Bristol, attempting to fly to Malaga, Spain, but was apprehended upon his return to London, where he sought to evade capture. The killer's defence claimed he had been attacked while trying to retrieve his stolen bicycle from another boy. The court also heard of his previous conviction for blade possession, having been caught with a lock-knife in a McDonald's restaurant a year prior to the killing. Prosecutor Simon Denison QC lamented Appleton's death as yet "another tragic waste of a young life" lost to knife violence. After the conviction, Det Ch Insp Chris Jones emphasized that "there can be absolutely no excuse for young people to carry such dreadful weapons on London's streets," highlighting how this case again demonstrates the dire repercussions.
Rupert Murdoch has appointed his two sons, Lachlan and James, to top roles at his media and entertainment empire.

Updated 6 October 2016, 16:36 BST. Over 500 African students displayed their newest inventions, among them a flying car prototype. BBC Africa met some to understand why they believe science is important. Video journalist: Christian Parkinson.

The Caerau hill fort, located close to Ely, is believed to have been inhabited by the Silurian tribe as early as the 5th Century BC. Excavations conducted last year, which saw 1,000 participants, indicated that the site's use might have extended into the late Roman period, or possibly beyond. The Caerau And Ely Rediscovering Heritage (Caer) Project is scheduled to continue until July 25. According to organisers, efforts at the site since 2011 have contributed to revising early Cardiff's history, uncovering an earlier occupation period for this hill fort, which features "massive" ramparts. Olly Davis, co-director of the Caer Heritage Project, noted that during the 2013 excavation, over 1,000 local residents visited, and an additional 120 directly participated in the archaeological efforts. He added that their goal for this year is to draw twice as many visitors, encouraging the people of South Wales to appreciate this significant site and acknowledge the remarkable communities residing nearby.
The annual Apprentice Boys parade has passed through the centre of Londonderry.
Soldiers could be deployed to events including the Chelsea Flower Show and the FA Cup final after the UK terror threat level was raised to critical.

In 2014, Kim Lennon alleged rampant drug smuggling at Lewes Prison, likening its sections to a "war zone." She was dismissed earlier this week after disciplinary proceedings but affirmed her intention to appeal and her lack of regret for speaking out. The Ministry of Justice (MoJ), however, asserted that Ms. Lennon's termination was not due to her whistleblower status.

Ms. Lennon had claimed in August 2014 that the drug Spice was being illicitly introduced into the jail. She explained that daily cell checks by officers were supposed to occur, but insufficient staff made this impossible, causing her to fear serious injury to an inmate or officer. At the time, the Prison Service denied unsafe staffing levels and stated a "zero-tolerance approach" to illegal substances.

Ms. Lennon's suspension occurred after she spoke with The Argus newspaper and the BBC. She stated that while speaking out had caused her significant distress, she had no regrets, adding that frontline officers are too afraid to speak due to potential repercussions. She lamented that she loved her job and felt she was being punished for doing what was right. She indicated her intention to appeal, but said she was approaching it one day at a time.

The MoJ declined to comment, citing the confidentiality of Ms. Lennon's dismissal. In a statement, the MoJ added that they did not wish to prejudice a possible appeal and emphasized their extremely serious approach to staff discipline. They further stated that any unprofessional behavior would be immediately investigated, leading to strong action, with serious wrongdoing being referred to the police. Disciplinary measures, they clarified, could range from a verbal warning to dismissal.

New figures from Northern Ireland Screen, the agency that has provided production funding for the HBO series, reveal that this program, parts of which are filmed in Northern Ireland, has received 24 Emmy nominations. Among these, two nominations acknowledge Northern Ireland-based production crew members. Ronan Hill, a prior Emmy winner in 2012, is once again nominated for outstanding sound mixing in a drama, and Carla Stronge for outstanding casting in a drama.

Since its inception in 2010, Northern Ireland Screen has invested Â£12.45 million into the series. This investment is estimated to have resulted in Â£110.7 million being spent on goods and services within the Northern Ireland economy. Between 2010 and 2014, Game of Thrones contributed an annual Â£21m to Â£23m to Northern Ireland's economy. These figures have undergone auditing. For the 2014-15 period, when Game of Thrones series five was filmed, NI Screen invested Â£1.6m, generating an estimated Â£22m in return.

The production of Game of Thrones takes place at Titanic Studios in Belfast and various other sites throughout Northern Ireland. During the series' production, numerous local businesses offer services, and several filming locations have evolved into popular tourist destinations. Damian Carr, representing Game of Thrones Tours, noted that enthusiasts from across the globe travel to visit the filming sites. He specified, "We've welcomed visitors from North and South America, various parts of Asia including China, Japan, Korea, and Taiwan, as well as throughout Europe. We initially offered one tour per week; now we conduct five."

Richard Williams, NI Screen's chief executive, affirmed that Game of Thrones has solidified Northern Ireland's reputation as a world-class hub for film and television production. He further stated that films and TV programs profoundly benefit tourism, contributing to a broader 'branding' of the region's people, society, and culture, which significantly inspires a desire to travel. He concluded, "There is no question that Game of Thrones is pioneering this 'set-jetting' trend, and we openly hope the series will achieve for Northern Ireland what The Lord of the Rings accomplished for New Zealand."

Individuals are accused of trafficking significant quantities of cocaine from Colombia to Europe via sailboats. Authorities reported a commander from the Colombian left-wing rebel group, Farc, was among those apprehended. Law enforcement indicated these suspects belonged to a transatlantic drug ring controlled by the 'Ndrangheta crime syndicate, headquartered in southern Italy. The inquiry, codenamed Santa Fe, was a collaborative effort involving Italian agents, the US Drug Enforcement Administration, and Spain's Guardia Civil. Officials stated the illicit network extended its operations to countries as diverse as Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Spain, and Montenegro. While the Farc commander's identity has not yet been publicly disclosed, Colombian media anticipate it will be revealed shortly. The rebel group largely finances itself through cocaine production and trafficking. During their investigations, a total of four tonnes of cocaine were confiscated. One of the most substantial seizures occurred overnight on 25-26 August last year, when the Spanish navy intercepted a sailboat headed for the Italian coast, discovering 856kg of cocaine on board. The drugs were reportedly smuggled from Colombia primarily to the southern Italian port of Gioia Tauro in Calabria, but also transported to northern Italian ports like Vado Ligure, Livorno, and Genoa. Police assert that the 'Ndrangheta operates Europe's largest cocaine smuggling network.

At 3 PM GMT on Prescot Road, a girl and a 55-year-old woman were struck by a black Ford Fiesta. The vehicle then collided with a lamp-post, and its two male occupants reportedly fled. The girl was hospitalized, and the woman is in serious but stable condition. Prescot Road was closed from Lugsmore Lane to Dunriding Lane.
Plans to develop a single strategy to regenerate Wrexham town centre have been drawn up.

Pearson's statement emerged just days after it announced the sale of the Financial Times to Japan's Nikkei. The company confirmed it was in discussions regarding a potential sale of its share in The Economist, though it stressed that a transaction was not guaranteed. While Pearson refrained from naming potential buyers, Italy's Agnelli family publicly stated its talks to increase its stake. Exor, the Agnelli family's investment arm, currently holds a 4.72% interest in the Economist Group. On its website, Exor affirmed that any expanded investment would remain a minority shareholding, reflecting its strong dedication to the editorial independence central to The Economist's character and achievement. It also reaffirmed the uncertainty of a final deal. Other notable shareholders in The Economist include the family dynasties of Cadbury, Rothschild, and Schroder. The Financial Times reported the 50% stake was valued at Â£400 million, with the sale likely to conclude over the summer. The Economist Group encompasses The Economist magazine, the Economist Intelligence Unit research company, and the US legislative information provider CQ Roll Call. Pearson had previously agreed to sell the Financial Times for Â£844 million as part of its group strategy to concentrate entirely on education.

Extradited from Slovakia, Zdenko Turtak previously admitted to rape and grievous bodily harm. In March, he assaulted a victim at a Beeston Road bus stop, dragging her behind a hedge to rape her before fleeing the UK. He faces sentencing on October 19 at Leeds Crown Court. On Thursday, prosecutors there dropped the attempted murder charge.

Neil Patrick Harris, known for his roles in "How I Met Your Mother" and "Gone Girl," is set to host 10 episodes of a new variety series for NBC, as reported by The Hollywood Reporter. Harris described the series, developed by British presenters Ant McPartlin and Declan Donnelly, as "a game changer." McPartlin, Donnelly, and Harris will also serve as producers for the as-yet-unnamed program, which is not expected to be a Saturday broadcast.

Originating in the UK in 2002, the show pays tribute to classic variety formats. It secured two Bafta awards this year, and international adaptations exist in Germany, Portugal, Italy, and Belgium. The program includes comedy sketches, musical and dance performances, and audience participation. Harris remarked that watching the show initially made him smile constantly, and after numerous seasons, his "face hurts." He added that its "unique structure aligns perfectly with my varied talents" and expressed eagerness to "get started and enjoy himself."

Harris recently completed his Broadway run in "Hedwig and the Angry Inch" and was recently named host of the 2015 Academy Awards. Last year, he hosted the Tony Awards for the fourth time, earning widespread praise for his hosting and his memorable opening performance.

A 24-year-old man, whose identity remains protected until he enters a plea, faces charges of sexually assaulting a teenager in a Johannesburg bar's restroom. Earlier this week, the alleged victim's family claimed Nelson Mandela's former spouse, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, dispatched her bodyguard to discourage them from pursuing legal action. The Mandela family has refrained from commenting. However, high-ranking members of the Mandela family, including Makaziwe Mandela, the former president's daughter, attended a short court session. His request for bail was adjourned until Tuesday, which means his name cannot be legally disclosed before that time. He has remained in custody since his arrest last Saturday. The BBC understands his defense will claim the encounter was consensual and that he was unaware of his accuser's age, given the pub's policy of not admitting individuals under 21. South African law stipulates that sexual activity with anyone under the age of 16 constitutes rape, irrespective of consent. According to BBC Southern Africa correspondent Karen Allen, the family of South Africa's first black president frequently finds itself under intense public scrutiny. Merely three months prior, another of his grandsons, Mandla Mandela, received a suspended sentence for assault after attacking a teacher following a road rage incident.
Nimble-fingered knitters have created a woolly version of an Essex town.
Former workers of a Fife paper firm have been awarded Â¬Â£1.5m in compensation after they were made redundant with just one day's notice.

This initiative stems from an increasing trend among oil and gas companies to deploy unmanned aerial systems (UAS) for offshore inspections and various other operations. These guidelines were collaboratively created by specialists in industry, aviation safety, and UAS operation. They outline optimal practices, operational procedures, and the necessary certifications to ensure adherence to UAS regulations.

Mick Borwell, Oil and Gas UK's health, safety, and environment director, observed that while the number is currently small, more oil and gas operators are increasingly utilizing UAS primarily for inspections, but also for aerial photography, surveying, and security purposes. This technology is especially appealing due to its capacity to enhance safety. For instance, deploying unmanned aircraft for inspections in confined spaces instead of human personnel significantly mitigates risks, proving both effective and efficient. We anticipate their deployment will expand.

Mr. Borwell stated that these new guidelines are intended to align with the existing safety and operational benchmarks already in place on the UK Continental Shelf for offshore oil and gas extraction and helicopter flight activities. He further explained that the objective is to prompt offshore operators considering this nascent technology to contemplate the complete offshore operating and safety framework, rather than focusing solely on the aerial vehicle itself.
Wigan half-back Sam Powell will miss Saturday's World Club Challenge match against Sydney Roosters after sustaining an ankle injury.
A man has denied murdering a pub-goer in a brawl on South Tyneside.

Proposed reductions to the council's animal welfare unit could restrict its duties solely to the mandatory collection of stray dogs. These plans have drawn a petition signed by over 2,000 campaigners. The authority highlighted a need to save Â£68 million from its total budget over the next four years. If approved, the cuts would also eliminate enforcement against dog owners who fail to clean up after their pets. The council announced these proposals will be debated at its full meeting on February 25th.

Kathryn Smith stated she received Â£52 weekly in income support, part of which she used to purchase a Class B substance. Jurors had previously learned of her apprehension that her 21-month-old daughter, Ayeeshia Jane Smith, might have suffered a seizure after ingesting drugs kept in their home. Both Ms. Smith and her ex-partner, Matthew Rigby, have pleaded not guilty to murder.

Ayeeshia, also known as AJ, died in 2014 at the coupleâs apartment in Burton-upon-Trent, Staffordshire. During questioning by prosecutors, 23-year-old Ms. Smith admitted she initially refrained from informing doctors treating Ayeeshia about her fears that the child had accessed drugs, as she worried they would perceive her as "a bad mother." She also explained her failure to notify police about the drugs in the house by stating she knew they were illegal. After Ayeeshia's death, approximately Â£30 worth of cannabis was discovered inside a Tommee Tippee plastic cup at the Britannia Drive property, but Ms. Smith claimed her daughter did not use that cup because it was broken.

The court heard that a senior social worker had reported Ms. Smith, of Sandfield Road, Nottingham, appearing "spaced out" during a home visit a week before Ayeeshia's collapse, although the child was not present at the time. Days before Ayeeshia's death, on April 17, 2014, two social workers attempted an on-the-spot drug search at the flat after smelling cannabis, but Ms. Smith refused to comply.

The prosecution also highlighted text messages Ms. Smith sent to Mr. Rigby and her parents, including one threatening her father on the day Ayeeshia died. Christopher Hotten QC, the prosecuting barrister, argued the message demonstrated her temper "on the day somebody killed your daughter in anger." However, Ms. Smith disputed this, asserting, "Nobody was angry on that day, or the day before that, nobody was being angry that day."

Jurors at Birmingham Crown Court were previously informed that Ayeeshiaâs death was caused by her heart being torn by a forceful stamp. Medical experts testified that such injuries are typically only found in victims of severe car crashes or individuals who have fallen from buildings. The trial continues.

The four-bedroom Georgian house served as the backdrop where eight-year-old Kevin McCallister, portrayed by Macauley Culkin, cleverly outwitted two clumsy burglars. The film generated over $477 million (Â£291 million) at the box office globally and spawned numerous sequels. John and Cynthia Abendshien, the property's owners, resided in the home during its production. They recounted that producer John Hughes' company had previously approached them to use their Winnetka, Illinois residence for his earlier film, *Uncle Buck*, but they had declined. Nevertheless, when a location scout returned eighteen months later for *Home Alone*, they agreed to transform their 1920s-built house into a movie set. Mr. Abendshien described Culkin, the child star, as "a nice, but quiet young boy." Christopher Columbus directed the movie, later going on to direct two *Harry Potter* films and *Percy Jackson & The Lightning Thief*. Producer Hughes, a prolific director throughout the 1980s, died of a heart attack two years ago.
A former RAF Spitfire pilot from Dorset has been remembering the "beautiful aircraft" in the week it celebrates its 75th anniversary.

On Saturday, a raid on a village in Yemen's Yakla district resulted in the deaths of up to 23 civilians, including ten children, according to the rights organization Reprieve. Yemeni sources indicated that Anwar al-Awlaki's daughter was among those killed; al-Awlaki himself was a militant who died in a 2011 US strike. This operation marked the first of its kind sanctioned by President Donald Trump. The US military initially reported that Navy Seal William "Ryan" Owens, 36, was killed and three others injured. However, the US Central Command (Centcom) subsequently stated that children might also be among the fatalities. According to the US military, several Apache helicopters participated in the mission, which resulted in the deaths of 14 militants, including three al-Qaeda leaders. White House spokesman Sean Spicer acknowledged to journalists that it is challenging to deem an operation a "complete success" when lives are lost or individuals are injured. He argued, however, that considering "the totality of what was gained to prevent the future loss of life," it was "a successful operation in all standards," notably omitting any reference to civilian casualties. Earlier that Thursday, Reprieve confirmed that a newborn was among the ten children who perished in the assault. The group further cited local accounts indicating that a heavily pregnant woman was shot in the abdomen during the raid, subsequently giving birth to an injured infant boy who tragically passed away. Shortly after the incident, images depicting deceased children began circulating on social media. Earlier in the week, Pentagon spokesman Capt. Jeff Davis advised reporters to treat "reports of female casualties with a grain of salt," suggesting they had been "trained to be ready and trained to be combatants." However, on Wednesday, the US military's Central Command conceded that "a number of civilians had been 'likely killed in the midst of a firefight'." On Thursday, Mr. Trump journeyed to Dover Air Force Base in Delaware to receive the remains of US Navy Seal William 'Ryan' Owens, who died in the raid. Al-Qaeda has capitalized on Yemen's ongoing civil war to fortify its presence in the nation's southern and southeastern regions. Over the last two years, Yemen has been consumed by conflict pitting forces loyal to the internationally recognized president, supported by a Saudi-led coalition, against Shia Houthi rebels.

Jay Rodriguez opened the scoring for Burnley just three minutes into the match, expertly heading home from a close-range Kieran Trippier cross. Despite later missing a penalty, awarded after Garath McCleary's foul on Ben Mee, Rodriguez quickly secured his second goal, again converting a cross from Trippier. For the home side, on-loan Wolves player Adlene Guedioura came closest to scoring, but his shot was directly saved by Burnley goalkeeper Lee Camp.

Rodriguez, who received his first professional contract from current Nottingham Forest manager Steve Cotterill during their shared time at Burnley, has now accumulated 16 goals across all competitions this season. In contrast, Forest, currently sitting 23rd in the league standings, has not managed a single goal at their City Ground stadium since November 19.

Speaking to BBC Radio Nottingham, Forest boss Steve Cotterill described the current period as "very, very difficult times." He explained that starting the game with a "makeshift back four" and then conceding so early made it an "uphill battle." Cotterill spoke highly of Jay Rodriguez, a "young boy" he knows "very, very well," emphasizing his effectiveness "in the box." Looking ahead, he confirmed the arrival of "a couple of loan signings," including "a good young player" and Danny Higginbotham, who will contribute "good experience and good leadership skills," indicating further team changes. Cotterill concluded by regretting they couldn't make these additions "two months ago" due to financial constraints, which has led to this "prolonged and painful time."

Reports indicate West Ham intends to increase their bid for the striker, who began his career at the east London club. At 34, Defoe has been a key player for Premier League strugglers Sunderland this season, scoring 11 goals in 21 appearances. His latest contributions came on Monday, helping Sunderland twice recover from a deficit to draw 2-2 with in-form Liverpool, a result that leaves manager David Moyes's side in 18th place.

Defoe's senior career started at West Ham before a Â£7 million move to rivals Tottenham in 2004, a deal that saw Bobby Zamora transfer the other way. He then joined Portsmouth for Â£7.5 million in January 2008, only to return to Spurs for Â£15 million the following year. A surprising move to Canadian team Toronto FC followed in 2014, until former Black Cats manager and ex-Spurs teammate Gus Poyet brought him to Sunderland in 2015.

BBC Radio 5 live's chief football correspondent, Ian Dennis, suggests West Ham will indeed test Sunderland's resolve again. However, it's considered inconceivable for the Black Cats to sell Defoe given their vulnerable league position. David Moyes recently described Defoe as "priceless," stressing that his goal-scoring ability will determine their top-flight survival. The rarity of proven, high-calibre goalscorers is precisely why West Ham is pursuing the 34-year-old. While money often influences decisions, Defoe's value to Sunderland's Premier League campaign is truly unparalleled.

During a crucial rugby match in Italy, Treviso's scrum-half Senioli gestured and smiled at Scott Williams, a Wales international for Scarlets, as he sprinted towards the try line. What seemed like a straightforward score turned into a costly mistake; Williams made Senioli regret his premature celebration by tackling him before he could cross the line. This incident highlights a recurring theme: Henry Senioli isn't the only athlete whose showboating has backfired.

Australian cyclist Simon Clarke, for instance, mistakenly thought he'd won a race in Italy and began celebrating by raising his arms. However, rival Giovanni Visconti quickly informed him that Davide Formolo had actually finished 22 seconds earlier.

In football, David Dunn's attempt at a 'rabona' â a complex skill where a player kicks the ball by wrapping one foot behind the other â went disastrously wrong. In front of a packed stadium, his misexecution led to an embarrassing fall.

Finally, French steeplechaser Mahiedine Mekhissi-Benabbad was disqualified and stripped of his European Championship gold medal. He had removed his shirt in celebration with only one hurdle remaining, but a protest from the Spanish team led to his disqualification from the competition.
MK Dons centre-back Scott Wootton will be out for up to nine months after rupturing his anterior cruciate ligament in Tuesday's EFL Trophy match against Barnet.

A study published in the Journal of Aesthetic Nursing reveals a rising inclination among individuals under 25 to receive anti-wrinkle injections. However, the findings indicate that such "frozen faces" might impede young people's ability to fully develop emotional expression. A prominent UK plastic surgery association deems the cosmetic use of Botox in teenagers to be "morally wrong." Botox, and similar neurotoxins, function by temporarily immobilizing muscles in the upper facial region, thereby diminishing wrinkles that appear during frowning.

Helen Collier, the nurse practitioner who conducted this research, attributes young people's aspiration for an "inexpressive frozen face" to the influence of reality television and celebrity culture. She highlights the widely recognized psychological concept of the facial feedback hypothesis, which posits that adolescents acquire social interaction skills by imitating others' facial expressions. Collier states that "our capacity as human beings to exhibit a broad spectrum of emotions is highly reliant on facial expressions." She adds that "emotions like empathy and sympathy are vital for our survival and for developing into self-assured, communicative adults." Nevertheless, she cautions that an increasing number of young individuals with "blank-faced" appearances might impair their capability to accurately express feelings. She warns, "Eliminating these expressions could impede their emotional and social maturation."

The study advocates for medical professionals to employ assessment instruments to determine if there are clear clinical justifications for administering Botox. While various assessment scales exist, evaluating factors such as skin thickness, sun damage, and wrinkle depth, experts caution that certain Botox clinics prioritize financial profit over patient well-being. Ms. Collier encourages therapists to devote time to enhancing young people's self-confidence instead of resorting to injections. She further states that "although the majority of the toxin's effects are temporary, studies indicate that muscles may not fully recover from the injections." She stresses, "It is crucial to comprehend the repercussions of initiating treatments at too young an age."

Dr. Michael Lewis, a psychology researcher at Cardiff University, explains that "the expressions we form on our faces influence the emotions we experience." He elaborates, "We smile due to happiness, yet smiling also generates happiness." He concludes that "medications like Botox inhibit a patient's ability to create specific expressions, potentially impacting our natural process of learning to feel emotions." Rajiv Grover, president of the British Association of Aesthetic Plastic Surgeons, asserts that "administering Botox to teenagers for cosmetic reasons is ethically indefensible and something no responsible practitioner would undertake." He warns, "This practice can only intensify body image concerns during a sensitive developmental period." Ms. Collier's findings are scheduled to be presented at the Clinical Cosmetic and Reconstructive Expo in October.

Ciaran James Williamson tragically died after an event at Craigton Cemetery in Cardonald on Tuesday, around 7:25 PM. He was pronounced deceased at Yorkhill Hospital; another ten-year-old involved is in stable condition there, while a third boy was later released. Police have stated the incident is not being treated as suspicious. Ciaran's family, in a police-issued statement, confirmed their son's tragic passing in what they called an accident at Craigton Crematorium, respectfully asking for privacy during this distressing time. Detective Inspector Tom McKean of Police Scotland expressed condolences to Ciaran's family, describing the circumstances as highly tragic. He added that inquiries are ongoing, but the event is not considered suspicious, and a full report will be submitted to the procurator fiscal.

The 72-year-old singer Barry Manilow was admitted to a Los Angeles hospital on Wednesday evening following a sold-out performance. His management team announced on Manilow's Facebook page that his hospitalization was due to complications from an operation he underwent on Monday. As a result, his next immediate tour dates have been postponed. An updated Facebook post indicated that Manilow has been ordered to avoid talking, singing, or rapping for the next 48 hours. However, those with tickets for the affected shows can use them for the rescheduled performances. The original Facebook statement advised ticket holders to keep their existing tickets for redemption on the new dates. It remains uncertain if Manilow will be able to attend Monday evening's Grammy Awards as scheduled. The New York-born artist, who rose to prominence in the 1970s, enjoys a global fanbase and is widely recognized for hits like "Mandy" and "Copacabana." He has faced various health challenges throughout his career, including needing ongoing dental treatment after a benign tumor ruptured in his mouth in 1986. His current "One Last Time, One Last Tour," which spans the UK and North America, is intended to be his final live concert series, concluding on June 23 at London's O2 Arena.

During his Open Championship debut at Royal Birkdale, 38-year-old Manley briefly held the lead, achieving a two-under-par score despite the challenging weather. A pleased Manley conveyed to BBC Radio Wales that he had initially considered par to be a respectable outcome for his first attempt. He concluded his round impressively, scoring an eagle three on the par-five 17th and a birdie on the final hole. Manley remarked that ending the round a couple of strokes under par felt 'great'. This strong finish marked a significant recovery from a nervous beginning, where he lost a stroke on the first hole after his opening drive at one of golf's major tournaments landed in the rough. He described feeling extremely anxious on the first tee, admitting he was 'shaking a little bit' due to the 'horrific' weather. He also mentioned difficulties warming up and a lack of rhythm while wearing his waterproof gear. Manley confessed it was likely the 'most nervous' he had ever been for a tee shot, but expressed optimism about understanding what to anticipate for the next day, hinting at a 'better game plan'. Manley, a professional golfer since 2003 and the sole Welsh competitor at Royal Birkdale, enjoyed considerable support from spectators. He noted the presence of friends from his local golf club, Mountain Ash, and his family, making his good score particularly satisfying for them. He admitted the achievement hadn't fully 'sunk in' yet, suggesting it might become real once he watched some golf later that evening, but confirmed he felt 'pretty chuffed'. Ranked 520th globally, Manley is scheduled to begin his second round on Friday at 11:47 BST. Despite his strong start, he is not adjusting his objectives for the week. He emphasized the need to 'plot your way around the course' due to the demanding links, stating he wouldn't allow his mind to 'wander'.

Police found Giuseppi Roncari deceased on Monday at 19:20 BST in Blackburn Street, Salford. Investigators stated that Mr Roncari, an Italian national, sustained injuries, leading them to treat his death as suspicious. While a post-mortem has been conducted, the precise cause of his death remains undetermined. Detective Inspector Andy Butterworth, from GMP's Major Incident Team, appealed for information, stating: 'Someone out there knows what occurred but has not yet contacted us.'

A dagger, part of a pair, was uncovered in 1925 by British archaeologist Howard Carter, tucked within the funerary linens of the young pharaoh Tutankhamun. The pristine, uncorroded iron blade's source remained a puzzle for researchers, as iron metallurgy was uncommon in ancient Egypt. Tutankhamun's mummification occurred over 3,300 years ago. A collaborative study by Italian and Egyptian researchers, published in the journal Meteoritics and Planetary Science, utilized a non-destructive X-ray method to verify the iron's makeup without causing harm. Daniela Comelli, the study's lead author, stated that "a significant nickel content unequivocally points to meteoritic iron." The team proposed that the combined levels of iron, nickel, and cobalt "strongly suggest an extraterrestrial origin" for the metal. By comparing the dagger's composition to known meteorites found within 2,000 km of Egypt's Red Sea coast, they identified one specific meteorite â which struck 150 miles (240 km) west of Alexandria â that exhibited comparable nickel and cobalt concentrations. According to the researchers, ancient Egyptians highly valued meteoritic iron, frequently using it for crafting exquisite ornamental or ceremonial items. Their findings indicate that Egyptians in the 13th century BCE already recognized that these unusual iron fragments descended from the heavens, a realization that predated Western understanding by over two millennia. The blade's superior craftsmanship, especially when contrasted with simpler meteoritic iron artifacts, "implies a remarkable proficiency in ironworking during Tutankhamun's reign," the team noted. This ornate dagger, boasting a decorated gold handle and a gold sheath adorned with a floral lily design on one face and a feather pattern on the other, is presently exhibited at the Egyptian Museum in Cairo.

Parliament has, for the first time, formally endorsed the commencement of the UK's departure from the EU by March's end following a vote by MPs. The government's chief whip appeared visibly pleased after the night's proceedings. This ministerial concession was, however, strategically astute; it secured Labour's support for the Article 50 activation timeline with only a nebulous pledge of a future plan, potentially as insubstantial as a brief scribble.

However, discontent simmers within Labour ranks regarding the handling of the issue, with reports of angry exchanges, suggesting some feel their leadership was outmaneuvered by the government's scheme. Pro-Remain Conservative dissenters remain highly skeptical of the government's underlying motives for providing further details on its Brexit strategy. Though they retreated today, their challenge is far from over.

Yet, beyond these immediate political maneuvers and the whip's evident satisfaction, the past 24 hours have underscored two crucial realities. Firstly, the vote's outcome indicates that very few MPs intend to outright obstruct Brexit or impede the process. While they will undoubtedly press the government for greater specificity and seek to modify any eventual proposals reaching the Commons, potentially causing disruption or delays, halting the departure entirely is not the objective for most.

Secondly, it's equally apparent that Prime Minister Theresa May lacks a stable majority on EU matters. Once her detailed plans are finally presented to Parliament, she will almost certainly be compelled to make concessions. This explains the government's strenuous efforts in the Supreme Court to prevent parliamentary intervention before complex negotiations in Brussels even commence.
